A hairy marine worm that lives under beach sand. Live bait for ocean fishing.
A moth in the third stage of its development into an adult. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
A small insect covered in a grey protective carapace. Is known to curl up in a ball when agitated. Live bait for ocean fishing.
A ball of crayfish and rye flour paste. Processed bait for freshwater fishing.
A ball of goby and rye flour paste. Processed bait for ocean fishing.
A common earthworm that earns its name from the blood red tint of its body. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
The thin tail of a rat, often carried by young Lalafellin boys as a good-luck charm. Bait for ocean fishing.
A tightly knitted wicker basket filled with a swarm of biting midges. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
A ball of crabmeat and rye flour paste. Processed bait for ocean fishing.
If allowed to pupate, this bright-yellow larva will transform into a hideous moth which can devour an entire tunic in a single turn of the sun. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
A ball of dark bass and sunset flour paste. Processed bait for freshwater fishing.
Also colorfully known as a “fisherman's member,” the stench of this sea-dwelling creature when sliced up is perfect for attracting hungry fish. Live bait for ocean fishing.
A tightly knitted wicker basket filled with a swarm of angry syrphids. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
A ball of Indigo herring and sunset flour paste. Processed bait for ocean fishing.
The honeyfly will lay its eggs in beehives where, upon hatching, the larvae will feed on honey until pupation. Live bait for freshwater fishing.

A spineless creature which hides patiently under the desert─ofttimes for several moons─until a larger beast passes nearby. The leech will then attach itself to the new host's leg and proceed to drink deep of the beast's blood until its belly is full, after which it releases itself back to the desert to wait for its next victim. Live bait for dunefishing.
This longhorn beetle larva can most commonly be found burrowed deep into the trunks of fallen logs. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
When night falls, thousands of these tiny scalekin can be seen scampering about the Sagolii Desert in search of the beetles on which they dine. Live bait for dunefishing.

It is not known why one end of these vilekin shines bright like a candle. It is, however, known that the light emitted by these creatures makes them a perfect target for hungry fish. Live bait for freshwater and ocean fishing.
When threatened, this tiny desert crustacean will curl itself into a ball which, to the untrained eye, will appear no more than a simple pebble. Live bait for dunefishing.
Unlike other vilekin larvae, the hoverworm is not confined to life on the ground. Filling its belly with air allows it to freely ride the thermals over the Sea of Clouds. Live bait for skyfishing.
Microscopic shrimp which inhabit the colder sea currents hailing from the northern seas. Live bait for ocean fishing.
The fact they are extremely difficult to harvest from their underwater homes makes fishing with caddisfly larvae an option for only the most well-to-do anglers. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
Atypical of common caterpillars, this sand-dwelling species is covered in a rock-like outer skin which serves to prevent the loss of moisture to the hot desert sun. Live bait for dunefishing.

With wings too underdeveloped for flying, this beetle has adopted another method of locomotion about the Sea of Clouds─a second bladder it fills with a noxious lighter-than-air gas. This foul stench is known to attract larger, hungrier creatures. Live bait for skyfishing.
A freshwater fishing lure made from a chocobo feather. The faint aroma of stable hay brings back memories of a simpler time.
A light plug lure made to resemble a minnow. Especially effective when used to land fish swimming close to the water's surface.
A polished brass lure shaped like a spoon so it will oscillate when dragged through the water, attracting fish. Especially effective in lakes.
A small metal cage packed with a pungent mixture of chopped shrimp. Fish are drawn to the area as pieces of shrimp break off from the cage. Processed bait for ocean fishing.
A caddisfly-shaped lure crafted from a crow feather. Recommended for freshwater fly fishing novices.
A polished silver lure shaped like a spoon so it will oscillate when dragged through the water, attracting fish. Especially effective in lakes.
The weight of this steel lure allows for casting great distances, such as from coastlines.
A heavy plug lure made to resemble a minnow. Effective in attracting fish from both surface and floor.
A freshwater fishing lure made from a snurble tuft.
The sheer weight of this steel lure allows for casting tremendous distances, such as from coastlines.
A metal river lure designed to resemble both a mayfly and a minnow, allowing for use in a variety of different situations.
A small metal cage packed with northern krill. Fish are drawn to the area as krill float off from the cage. Processed bait for ocean fishing.
A polished mythril lure shaped like a spoon so it will oscillate when dragged through the water, attracting all manner of lake and marsh life.
A freshwater lure made from a wildfowl feather. Its uncanny resemblance to a mayfly makes it irresistible to vilekin-feeding fish such as trout.
A light freshwater lure crafted to resemble a frog. Best suited for larger prey such as pikes and certain trout.
A shiny blacklip oyster shell lure shaped like a spoon so it will oscillate when dragged through the water, attracting all manner of aquatic life. Especially effective in lakes.
Several small spinners joined together to resemble a school of fish. Especially effective in rivers.
A freshwater fly designed to sink below the water's surface, and by doing so, attract the larger carnivorous fish living near the floor.
A curved man-made lure used traditionally in the Far East, the name means literally “bow horn.” Increases chances of landing a big catch, even when casting from shore.
Increases EXP earned by 20% when level 10 and below.
Increases EXP earned by 20% when level 10 and below.
Increases EXP earned by 20% when level 10 and below.

Fits: Game Masters
A wooden mask used in Padjali ceremonies. A rough translation of the word monoa is “to sit silently on the land and speak.”

Powdered coral gives this medicinal concoction the deep amber tone from which it gets its name. It is distributed to members of the Lominsan Armada during battle to provide quick recovery from physical wounds.

column5: When taken internally, this blend of rare forest herbs stimulates the mind, allowing for immediate recovery of MP. Conjurers serving alongside Gridania's Wood Wailers and the Gods' Quiver often use the potion in the field during battle when there is not enough time to recover naturally.
This fragrant fusion of aromatic oils has long been used by the Brass Blades of Ul'dah to instantly rejuvenate both body and mind.
This alchemically crafted restorative instantly cures most instances of poison.
This alchemically crafted restorative instantly cures most instances of blindness.
This alchemically crafted restorative instantly cures most instances of silence.
This alchemically crafted restorative instantly rouses most sleeping targets.
This alchemically crafted restorative instantly cures most instances of paralysis.
The properties of this solid-gold needle include curing petrification and pricking fingers.

The billowy plumage of the fledgling Phoenix─a legendary bird that, upon each fiery death, is said to rise from its own ashes in a literal “blaze of glory.” When placed upon the body of one who is incapacitated, it will instantly revive the person. While some cultures insist that the tailfeather's restorative properties trump those of down, these claims have yet to be proven in any sort of scientific capacity.

※Cannot be used during battle.

Everyone knows this elementally charged concoction slightly increases resistance to fire-aspected damage. What few people know, however, is that after long periods of disuse, the liquid undergoes a natural alchemical transformation that grants it the same coloring properties as common dye.

Cannot be opened in instanced areas such as dungeons, PvP areas, or raids.

A lean cut of meat taken from below a sheep's rib cage.
A lean piece of meat taken from under the short ribs of a dodo.
A fist-sized chunk of lean, bloody meat cleanly sliced from the carcass of a pesky mole.
Sinewy meat taken from the tail of a salamander.
A whole young dodo, small enough to fit in most conventional household ovens.
A tender piece of meat taken from the breast of a chicken.
A tough piece of meat taken from the upper leg of an antelope.
A large, tender slab of meat taken from the shoulder of an aldgoat.
An extra-lean, tough piece of meat taken from the leg of a raptor.
A cut of tender, lean meat taken from the rear back of a buffalo.
Sinewy meat taken from the tail of an eft.
The soft liver of a deepwater orobon.
A fat megalocrab leg, bursting with sweet, juicy meat.
The egg of a domesticated chicken.
The heavy egg of a wild dodo.
The lightweight egg of a puk.
The large egg of a wild apkallu.
This dark green variety of seaweed found in all five of Eorzea's seas has been known to grow up to a malm in length.
A pungent bulb vegetable native to the Near East.
A long orange root vegetable commonly grown in the rocky alpine soil of the Coerthas region.
A bright-orange squash which sweetens in flavor when cooked.
Though many botanists claim this tangy blood red specimen is more closely related to a fruit than a vegetable, it is widely accepted across Eorzea as the latter.
A long white root vegetable indigenous to the mountainous region of Coerthas.
A crisp leafy vegetable native to the plains of La Noscea.
An iron-rich leafy vegetable native to the Cieldalaes.
Oft used as a garnish in other dishes, this pungent vegetable grows in abundance in the mountainous region of upper La Noscea.
A pepper which can be dried and ground to make a mild red spice. It is often used in medicines, as well as in cooking.
An edible oval-leaved cactus brought back by explorers of the New World.
A starchy tuberous vegetable originally introduced to Eorzea by explorers from the distant western continent.
A firm purple-skinned vegetable indigenous to the mountains of the Near East. A common wives' tale claims if you eat too many of this vegetable, you will turn into one.
A round leafy vegetable which prefers the steady climate of the Black Shroud.
A thick spiny-leaved cactus indigenous to the southern continent of Meracydia. The Miqo'te are known to treat severe burns with the cool gel-like substance found inside the leaves.
A long, pungent, leafy vegetable that lacks a bulb like that of its cousin, the onion.
This long, thin variety of squash earns its name from its resemblance to the horn of a mountain ram.
The leaf-like bud of an artichoke plant. Due to the roughness of its petals, only the fleshy lower portions can be consumed, as well as the center of the bud, commonly known as the “heart.”
The underdeveloped sporeling of a funguar.
An edible mushroom known for its leaf-like appearance as well as its fruit-like fragrance.
This tiny round mushroom has a cap which resembles a coin, and is known for its rich flavor and pungent aroma.
A small white mushroom commonly found in moist areas across Eorzea.
A rare white mushroom that grows in the soil, rather than above it, making the specimen almost impossible to locate. It is treasured as a delicacy for its unique aroma.
The underdeveloped “sporeling” of a myconid. Popular myth has that rats will use the chair-shaped fungus as a place to rest.
A rare black mushroom that grows in the soil, rather than above it, making the specimen almost impossible to locate. It is treasured as a delicacy for its unique aroma.
The shell which encases this walnut is reminiscent of the (now fallen) lesser moon of its namesake.
The ghostly white shell which encases this walnut is reminiscent of the celestial body of its namesake.
This seed of the kukuru tree is the primary ingredient in chocolate.
The seed of an olive tree, often preserved in brine or pressed to make oil.
The seed of a chestnut tree, this savory nut is covered in a coat of prickly spikes.
The seed of a walnut tree, this fragrant nut is covered by a thin, fleshy outer shell and a hard inner shell.
The seed of an oak tree, this small nut is covered by an extremely hard outer shell.

A semisweet variety of grape which has adapted to the volcanic soil abundant on Vylbrand.

The fruit of a sunflower, this small seed is covered by a thin black shell.
A common variety of green bean recognizable by its long thin pods. Buffalo are said to be fond of the beans, and have been known to eat entire crops if left unchecked.
This grain is imported from a land far to the east. When cooked, it has a consistency slightly more glutinous than normal rice.
Thin round beans resembling tiny convex lenses. Thought to have been introduced to Eorzea by the realm's first Lalafellin settlers.
Hundreds of sweet yellow kernels adorn each cob of this vegetable native to the recently discovered New World.
Sweet green beans recognizable by their thin, crescent-shaped pods.
A dark variety of rye grass commonly found growing in the higher elevations of Mor Dhona and Coerthas.
A common variety of golden-brown wheat eaten as a staple in many of Eorzea's city–states.
Coarsely milled rye.
Finely milled sunset wheat.
Coarsely milled millioncorn.
The sweet-smelling bark of the cinnamon tree is often dried and ground into a spice used to add flavor to confectionaries, though it is also commonly used in medicines.
A pungent spice used to flavor many different varieties of dishes. It is also thought to ward off vampiric bats, but there is no evidence to substantiate that claim.
An aromatic spice used in cooking as well as pickling.
A sweet-smelling spice made from the dried buds of the clove tree. It is used to flavor confectionaries, and as an essential oil.
A sweet-smelling herb used in cooking and in medicines.
A sweet-smelling spice made from the dried pod of the rare vanilla plant. It is often used in the making confectionaries as well as medicines.
A leafy herb with a crisp, fragrant aroma. It is often used in cooking and in teas, as well as for its essential oil.
When dried and ground into a fine powder, this yellow-tinged spice can add quite the kick to any dish.
An exotic root vegetable native to the Far East that is often dried, ground, and used in cooking as well as in the creation of medicines.
A fragrant herb used to flavor various meat and poultry dishes.
A red-hot spice known to cause severe burns in the mouths of those who consume too many.
A savory spice made from the dried leaves of the laurel bush, or as it is known by some, the yanny bush.
The young leaves of the mugwort plant are used not only as a spice in cooking, but also as a curative agent in various unguents.
A fragrant herb used to flavor various meat and poultry dishes.
A tear-shaped nut which can be used to season exotic sweets, or pressed for its fragrant oil.
This spice made from the dried styles of the desert saffron flower gives a bright-yellow color to dishes.
A sweet-smelling seed that is ground into a powder and used to flavor pastries and tea. It is also widely used in Far Eastern medicines.
A savory herb often found growing in parched desert environments. It is used in cooking and various medicinal ointments and unguents.
These leaves, when dried and steeped in hot water, create a sweet-smelling tea known for its curative properties.
Finely ground salt used not only for flavoring foods, but for pickling and preserving as well.
Crystallized sugar made from boiling down maple syrup.
A sweet, dark liquid made by boiling down maple sap.
Bees make this sweet golden honey from the nectar of flowers.
Sweet, snow-like sugar, perfect for dusting Starlight Celebration sweets.
The butterfat-rich layer skimmed off of buffalo milk. Widely used in confectionaries.
A smooth, fatty cream made by churning buffalo milk.
A thick oil extracted from kukuru beans. Used in making chocolate.
Roasted kukuru beans ground into a fine powder. Used in making chocolate.
Clove-infused cooking oil.
A fragrant light-green oil extracted from pressed olives.
Lavender-infused cooking oil.
A fruity vinegar made from fermenting faerie apples.
A high-quality distilled vinegar made from select lowland grapes.
Simple pie dough made of flour and butter.

Made from lowland grapes grown on arid soil, this vinegary wine is more suited to cooking than it is to drinking (though that does little to stop most Lominsan pirates from drowning their sorrows in the phenolic seepage).
A clear gelling agent extracted from animal skin and fish bones.
Broth created from boiling down the flesh and bones of various types of seafood.
A tangy sauce made from crushed tomatoes.
A mixture of dried bread, nuts, and fruit, blended with several savory spices.
A clear golden broth made by boiling chicken bones.

A leafy vegetable indigenous to the Near East. While too bitter for most people's tastes, chocobos are known to enjoy the flavor, and thus the greens are often used as fodder for the animals.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by offering multiple servings)
A vividly striped saltwater fish commonly found in the Strait of Merlthor.
These small saltwater fish form massive schools resembling colossal sea creatures to discourage predators from approaching.
A common saltwater shrimp found in the plankton-rich waters of the Sea of Jade.
A semi-transparent jellyfish commonly found in the Strait of Merlthor, where it goes through nine separate stages of development before reaching adulthood.
A purple, spiny, slug-like creature found in the shallows off of the island of Mazlaya, and treasured in the Far East as a delicacy.

This particular variety of herring will gather in busy harbors to feed on the small sea creatures which consume the waste dumped from ships.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]
A tasty bivalved mollusk commonly found on and near the island of Bianaq.

A colorful saltwater fish commonly found in the warm seas around the island of Bianaq. Not known for its flavor, the wavekin is most often kept as a pet.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]
A flat bottom-feeder commonly found in the relatively calm waters of Moraby Bay.
A small bluish-grey crab found in tide pools along the La Noscean coast.

A striped saltwater fish indigenous to the cold northern waters of the Bloodbrine Sea.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]
This saltwater wavekin, most commonly found in the shallows of the Strait of Merlthor, is protected by a hard shell resembling a helmet.

Also known as the milk of the sea, these tasty bivalve mollusks can be found on sea rocks all around Eorzea, but it is said the plumpest, most succulent grow in the nutrient-rich waters of the Rothlyt Sound.
These thin, long saltwater fish will oft jump out of the water and glide for yalms across the surface, using their pectoral fins as ersatz wings.

A small colorful fish native to the warmer waters of the seas near Meracydia. Since the Calamity, more and more have been caught off Eorzea's southern coastline.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
A long bivalved mollusk most commonly found buried in the beaches of islands situated in the Rhotano Sea. They are known to leap out of their burrows when surprised or agitated.

The somber blue tone of its skin does not make this variety of octopus any more docile than its crimson cousins. It is a crafty hunter who lurks in the shadows, snatching unwary prey and strangling it with its powerful eight arms before shredding it with its razor-sharp beak.

A saltwater fish that, when provoked, blows up to three times its normal size to intimidate the would-be attacker. It is also known to have an organ which contains a potent silencing poison.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
This tiny saltwater fish travels in giant schools through the Indigo Deep searching for food. Its razor-like fins have been known to cut straight through the strongest of fishing nets.
A large saltwater wavekin that roams the Rhotano Sea in small schools, preying on smaller fish such as anchovies or sardines.
This deep-sea-dwelling wavekin attracts its prey with a tiny glowing appendage protruding forth from its disfigured head, and then swallows the poor victim whole with its unnaturally large mouth.
When swimming upright, this strange sea creature closely resembles a riding chocobo, hence the name.
A cherry-colored saltwater fish found in abundance in all of Eorzea's five seas, though it is said those caught near Bianaq are the largest.
A flat bottom-feeder commonly found in the frigid waters of the Bloodbrine Sea.

A ravenous shark with a hammer-shaped head it uses to quickly detect its prey. This wavekin is most commonly found living in small schools in the Strait of Merlthor.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
A blue, spiny, slug-like creature found in the shallows off of Vylbrand, and considered a delicacy by Sea Wolves.

This blue-backed, white-bellied saltwater fish native to the Indigo Deep is known to migrate in large schools from north to south in the winter, and back again in the summer.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
A large saltwater fish known to migrate between the Sea of Jade and the Sea of Ash. In recent years, overfishing by boats from the Far East has led to a significant drop in their numbers.
Though once found all across the five seas, seadragon numbers are now but a mere fraction of what they once were, due in part to Ishgardian culling parties.

A tiny saltwater fish native to the waters of Vylbrand. Unlike other wavekin, they feed only at night, their activity increasing as Menphina waxes.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
A tasty saltwater fish indigenous to the cold waters of the Bloodbrine Sea. Its name comes from a legendary northern king who it was said would only eat the fatty flesh of this wavekin.
A bivalved mollusk found on the cliffs and rocks lining the Rhotano Sea. On rare occasions, sand will become trapped inside the shell and gradually form into a pearl.
A violet-hued fish found in the warmer waters of Eorzea's southern seas.
A saltwater fish covered in scores of sharp spines, discouraging would-be predators from dining on this otherwise defenseless fry.

A large, spindle-shaped shark commonly found in the Sea of Ash and known to attack without provocation.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 4 and higher.]
A razor-fanged saltwater fish known to migrate throughout the warm waters of the Sea of Ash, following the schools of shrimp on which it feeds.

A deep-blue freshwater fish native to the lakes and swamps of the Black Shroud. They can be seen sticking their heads out of the water whenever it rains, leading people to believe it is the fish summoning the storm. However, naturalists have surmised that the fish are simply rising to the surface in search of food, mistaking the drops of water for insects.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

A giant cephalopod characterized by its spectacular whorling shell. Commonly found in the nutrient-rich Bay of Dha'yuz, the wavekin are thought by sailors and pirates to be the heralds of the Navigator, Llymlaen, and their shells are often carved into celebratory chalices.
When stretched straight from head to tail, the longest of saltwater pike eels can measure more than a full yalm in length.

This saltwater fish's name comes from the odd lump on its head, thought to resemble a mummer's motley cap.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
A bottom-feeding flatfish, the plaice is most commonly found blending into the sands covering the sea floor near the Isles of Umbra.

Legends tell of giant sea devils emerging from the sea to wrap their many arms around ships and drag them to the abyss. This seems impossible today, as the largest catches in recent memory are little more than a yalm across.
A large crimson crustacean commonly found hiding in the rocks off the shores of islands dotting the Rhotano Sea. The rich, flavorful tails are regarded as a delicacy across Eorzea.
A large-mouthed saltwater glutton, thought to feed on most anything, from smaller fish, to seaweed, to the flesh of drowned sailors.

Despite the modifier, the little Thalaos is anything but small; though compared to the Thalaos of legend, even the largest of sea serpents would be deemed “little.” Normally only found far offshore in the Indigo Deep, this rare wavekin can sometimes be found swimming near the eastern cliffs of La Noscea.
This enormous bivalved mollusk is easily recognizable by the unique wave pattern found on its outer shell.

This deep-sea predator is not only massive, but deceptively fast. Some sailors swear that a mahi-mahi can make the journey from Meracydia to the Cieldalaes in less than a fortnight, though knowing most sailors, that claim may be slightly exaggerated.
While similar to the sole or plaice in appearance and behavior, the halibut is much larger than both, and can feed a Lalafellin family of five for several turns of the sun.

A large saltwater fish found in the warm waters south of the Sea of Ash and known for its remarkable swimming speed.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 4 and higher.]

An ancient species of saltwater fish which appears to have flourished in times well before the Allagans built their empire.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
This rarely seen giant cephalopod makes an appearance in ancient Sea Wolf mythology as the creature on which the legendary whale Bismarck fed.

A legendary cephalopod feared by sailors young and old. Tales of these cyclopean creatures tearing up ships and dragging them down to the abyss can still be heard in alehouses and inns across Hydaelyn.
Legends say this giant saltwater fish will help those stranded in the water by allowing them to ride it back to shore.

A legendary saltwater fish covered in thick armor and said to have once been worshipped by the Sahagin.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 4 and higher.]

A legendary shark with a mouth so big and an appetite so large, it is said it can swallow an adult Roegadyn whole.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 4 and higher.]

Legends say that this gargantuan saltwater fish once ripped a hundred-man galleon in two with its saw-like head.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 4 and higher.]
A brown-carapaced freshwater crustacean commonly found in the rivers and lakes of Aldenard.

A common freshwater fish found in rivers across Eorzea. Prefers the slow-moving waters found near a river's mouth to the rapids found upstream.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]
A brightly striped freshwater fish native to the rivers and lakes of the Coerthas and Mor Dhona regions.
An undersized variety of catfish found in still, swampy waters across Aldenard.
A white-carapaced freshwater crustacean commonly found living in caves or deep lakes where sunlight is absent.
Unlike other freshwater trout which make their habitat in swift-flowing rivers, the silver princess trout prefers the relative seclusion of inland lakes.
A hardy species, the dusk goby can survive not only in freshwater, but also the mouths of rivers, where the tides can bring saltwater malms inland.
A fierce freshwater fish most commonly found in Gridania's Jadeite Flood and Black Tea Brook.
A crimson-carapaced freshwater crustacean commonly found in the streams and lakes of Vylbrand.
Each night, this freshwater fish will use its fins to dig a shallow burrow in river or lake beds, where it will sleep, relatively safe from predators.
This long, thin, brass-colored freshwater fish is most commonly found in the Yafaem Saltmoor and surrounding rivers and lakes.
Large schools of these dark silver fish can be found in the White Maiden and her tributaries.
A tiny freshwater fish native to the lakes and rivers fed by runoff from Abalathia's Spine.
Commonly found in the sea caves and grottoes of Vylbrand, the eyes of this freshwater fish regressed long ago, earning the specimen its name.

An amphibious fish which can survive for bells out of water as long as its skin remains moist. When on land, the mudskipper uses its pectoral fins to “wander” about in search of shelter. Because of this trait, the fish is sometimes associated with the god Oschon.
Found in the crystal-clear rivers and lakes of Mor Dhona and Coerthas, this fish's scales reflect all seven colors of the rainbow, making it difficult to locate in the water.
A tiny freshwater crustacean commonly found in rivers throughout Eorzea.
A beautiful blue freshwater fish known for its violent disposition.
A common freshwater fish found in rivers and lakes in almost every corner of Eorzea. A staple for many of the realm's smallfolk.

Believed to have hitched a ride on the hull of a trade ship, the acorn snail is an invasive species originally from the New World, far to the west. As it has few natural predators in Eorzea, its numbers have exploded in recent years.

A small freshwater fish originally from the eastern continent of Othard. It is said that the first dark sleeper was introduced to Eorzea by an exiled Lalafellin prince who wished to once again experience the luxuries of his homeland.
A fair-sized freshwater fish found distributed evenly throughout the lakes and rivers of lower Vylbrand.
This freshwater fish is found in lakes and marshes throughout the Black Shroud...but rarely in moats.

The copperfish's dull orange scales─a hue rare in freshwater wavekin─make this species popular amongst Ul'dahn nobles, who apparently prefer even their fish to be the color of their coin.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]

Hatched far up inland rivers, bluebell salmon will travel all the way downstream to the Indigo Deep where they will spend the majority of their adulthood. Then, however, when it comes time to spawn, they will return back upstream to the place of their birth.
As its name implies, the mudcrab spends most of its life in the muddy freshwater shallows of swamps and moors.

Patches of gold, silver, and bronze cover this medium-sized freshwater fish's body, making it a favorite choice for the private garden pools of Ul'dahn nobles.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
The grip of this tiny freshwater crustacean's claw is so strong, it has been the end of many a Lalafell's fingers...and more. Take care when handling.
Similar to salmon, this green-grey freshwater eel lives the majority of its life in the salty waters of the sea, returning to inland rivers to only spawn and die.
This bivalved freshwater mollusk with a tear-shaped shell can be found either clinging to the side of submerged boulders or simply lying half-buried in the mud.

This freshwater fish was once found only in the waters heated by the flows of lava coursing beneath the mighty volcano O'Ghomoro. After the Calamity, however, fishers began finding the wavekin in other warm locations such as Thanalan.
With an almost completely transparent body, this variety of freshwater perch is coveted by naturalists wishing to study the inner workings of organs on a living specimen.
Four-eyed fish do not actually have four eyes, but two eyes that are divided into an upper and lower portion that allow the wavekin to see both above and below the water at the same time.
Black eels reach maturity in the Sea of Jade, at which point they return back up the Velodyna and Hathoeva rivers to spawn.

This freshwater fish, known for its voracious appetite, is originally native to the southern continent of Meracydia.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

Whereas other shrimp shed their old exoskeletons each summer in favor of new ones, the aegis shrimp simply adds a new layer every year until the shell is so hard, not even a blow from a trained pugilist can break through it.
This freshwater fish commonly found in the rivers of the Black Shroud will often grow no larger than a mere five ilms.
Though not amphibious like the mudskipper, the climbing perch will jump from Black Shroud rivers onto low-lying tree branches in order to catch flies and beetles.
A large whiskered fish that can be found in the calm marshes of the Black Shroud.
Native to the rivers and lakes of the Black Shroud, this freshwater fish uses electric receptors on its body to locate food.
A long, ugly freshwater eel found in nearly every river and lake in Eorzea. Its toothy grin is enough to frighten children across the realm.
This variety of freshwater fish has the queer habit of wearing the skulls of small drowned animals, though it is not known exactly why.
This freshwater fish matures in the salty waters of the Bloodbrine Sea, only to return up the Yugr'am River where it was born to spawn.
Tiny white spots cover the body of this rare freshwater fish.
As it has the tendency to coil up while inactive, this variety of freshwater eel is oft mistaken for lost boat rigging.

A rare type of fish oft found in stagnant waters such as the isolated pools which collect in the basin of Empty Heart on the western finger of the Gods' Grip.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]
A freshwater snail that survives solely on the carrion of animals that get caught and perish in the sucking mud of swamps and marshes.
A small fish that is found only in Rootslake in the Black Shroud.

A single flat tooth on the bottom of this freshwater species' mouth gives the bonytongue its name.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
The claws of this freshwater crustacean are covered in myriad tiny bristles which provide the illusion that the crab is wearing mittens.
A giant freshwater fish found in the tepid rivers and lakes of the Black Shroud.
The flesh of this freshwater trout native to central and northern Eorzea is a bright pink, leading to the common nickname, “cherry trout.”
An amphibious fish capable of breathing on land. This trait has allowed it to adapt to life in the deserts of Thanalan.
As are copperfish and goldfish, freshwater silverfish are prized amongst well-to-do Ul'dahns, and often kept as pets.

Bright patterns, similar to a clown's motley, cover this small freshwater fish from head to tail.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
The rock-hard scales of the armored pleco are thought to protect the wavekin from injury when being dashed about swift water rapids.
Significantly larger than a dark bass, landing a giant bass can prove quite the challenge for even the most seasoned angler.
This scarlet cousin to the maiden carp can most commonly be found in the Velodyna and Hathoeva rivers.
A cousin of the sea-dwelling balloonfish, spotted puffers are unique in that they can survive in the brackish waters of deltas and river mouths.
Truly a prize, this bright-gold fish, though rare, can be found in rivers and lakes across Eorzea.
This freshwater eel native to the rivers and lakes of Thanalan will often display the unique trait of swapping its mate with other nearby eels when spawning.

A red-scaled trout commonly found in the rivers originating on Abalathia's Spine.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

A colorful freshwater fish that can only survive in rivers located in more temperate climes.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
A species of trout native to Vylbrand's Bronze Lake.
The fiery red shells of this freshwater snail are prized by the Amalj'aa, and are useful when bartering with the beast tribe.
This variety of striped freshwater fish earns its name from its tendency to gather by the legs of any man or beast who enters its habitat.
A rare freshwater fish decorated with a thunderbolt-like pattern down its back.

Fall jumpers are born with an inherent tendency to swim against the current. When they arrive at a falls, this leaves them with no option but to leap out of the water in an attempt to continue upstream.
The freshwater knifefish is named such due to its resemblance to a flat blade.
A giant freshwater fish found in inland lakes and rivers. Its name is derived from its resemblance to a knotty oaken root.
This freshwater fish has highly developed fins and spines which not only protect the wavekin, but serve as weapons for hunting its prey.
Though classified as a freshwater fish native to the Velodyna and Hathoeva rivers, this particular wavekin can survive in the brackish delta where the waterways spill into the Sea of Jade.
Though classified as a freshwater fish native to the White Maiden, this particular wavekin can survive in the brackish waters where the Maiden meets the Strait of Merlthor.

Similar to the spotted puffer, the kobold puffer can also survive in the brackish waters of deltas and river mouths. Its spots, however, are replaced with a hideous coat of bristly spines which give it the appearance of a bedraggled kobold.

When feeding, the archerfish will lift its head ever so slightly above a lake or river's surface and spit a stream of water up to a yalm to strike flies from low-lying branches into the water with remarkable accuracy.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

The goblins claim that they brought this variety of perch back from their years-long pilgrimage into Othard and Ilsabard...because it tasted so divine.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
A rare species of carp native to the Agelyss River.
A violent species of freshwater fish from central Abalathia's Spine that will attack other assassin betta if they draw too near while feeding.

Similar to its cousin the mudskipper, the sludgeskipper can also survive outside water for several bells. The sludgeskipper, however, is at home in highly polluted pools where other creatures would likely perish.
This freshwater anomaly possesses high concentrations of lightning-aspected aetherial energy which can be used to inflict serious injury on any foolish enough to provoke the fish.
A hard-scaled freshwater fish native to southern Eorzea.
Unlike its Eorzean cousins, the Ilsabardian bass is mean-tempered and quick to bite, attacking other species sharing the same lake until there are none left but its own.

A brightly colored freshwater fish native to the warm waters in and around the Amalj'aa territory of Paglth'an.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
The largest pleco known to naturalists, this variety is known for violently flailing its fins at any unfortunate creature that happens to swim by.

Native to the freshwater rivers of Abalathia's Spine, the kissing trout is famous for its mating “dance” in which a male and female will face each other for several moments before proceeding to couple.
While all species of freshwater pike are known to be violent, this particular variety has been recorded actually biting the ankles of wading fishers.

The brilliant luster of this freshwater fish native to the Far East has made it a popular addition to the aquariums and garden ponds of Ul'dahn patricians.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

Just as its name implies, the vampire lampern is indeed a sucker of blood, using its multiple rows of teeth to latch onto its prey, whether it be sea or land creature, and bore a hole from which to drink.

Legend states that this particular variety of sculpin is a favorite of Oschon, the Wanderer, and that the god will oft dine on this fish while on His journeys through the realm of man.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
It is said that not even a fishing line made from adamantite wire can withstand the cutting force of this legendary giant crustacean's claws.
Two front teeth of this freshwater fish are exceptionally long and therefore protrude from the mouth, giving them the appearance of coeurl fangs.
A giant freshwater fish native to the rivers and swamps of La Noscea.
This freshwater fish has a bright-yellow sun-like pattern across its body, giving rise to the name “sundisc.”
A legendary freshwater fish said to have a head not unlike that of an alligator, complete with rows of razor-sharp teeth.
It is believed that after living in waters tainted with wootz ore for so long, this knifefish absorbed so much of the mineral that it began showing in its scales.
A giant freshwater fish found throughout Aldenard and known for the decidedly feline whiskers which it uses to detect the movement of prey.
Neither dead nor necrophagous, the cadaver carp is called such because of where it chooses to live─some of the most tainted, noisome, and foul waters in all of Eorzea.

This amazing crab will rub its shell up against funguars to collect spores, which it will then grow on its back. Once the sporelings begin to sprout, the crab will use its claws to slice off the mushrooms and eat them.

Named after the primal Ramuh's signature weapon, this strange freshwater fish will only feed when the weather is rainy.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
The rock-hard scales of this variety of freshwater garpike are spattered with scores of unhealthy-looking spots.

This giant freshwater fish lives out its adulthood feeding in the Indigo Deep before returning all the way back up to the head of the White Maiden to spawn.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
Record of the bowfin being caught in the Black Shroud dates back to the time of the first Elezen settlers.
A flat freshwater bottom-feeder found predominantly in marshes and swamps, where it can hide under the blanket of organic detritus collected on the floor.

A legendary giant freshwater fish indigenous to the lands of the Far East. The takitaro found in Eorzea are thought to be the offspring of a specimen presented as a gift to an eccentric sultan who loosed the fish into a cenote when it grew too large to keep in the royal aquariums.
A legendary giant freshwater fish rumored to live in the bottomless swamps hidden deep within the unexplored regions of the Black Shroud.
A giant freshwater fish so shrouded in mystery that naught is known of it.
It is rumored that a jungle catfish can grow to become as large as an aurochs, and while there are sightings aplenty of these massive specimens, one that large has yet to be caught.
A tiny sand-dwelling fish which can spend its whole life out of the water.
A large variety of air-breathing catfish. Its near-frictionless scales allow it to “swim” through the desert as a normal fish would through the water.
When threatened, this sand-dwelling fish will beat the ground with its fins, kicking up a cloud of dust and allowing it the opportunity to escape unscathed.
These sand-dwelling fish will skip across the desert unless they are fortunate enough to stumble across a sandstorm, in which case they will spread their fins and ride the storm great distances.
This sand-dwelling slug is able to maintain its mucous coating by absorbing the moisture from prey it catches at the bottom of conical pits not unlike the ones antlions are known to dig.
Remarkably smooth skin allows the dune manta to glide through desert sand as if it were the sea.
Cloud jellyfish aimlessly drift about the Sea of Clouds, tentacles spread out below them, searching for the small birds on which they feed.

One of the more common creatures found living on the thermal currents above the Sea of Clouds, from a distance, the skyfish appears to be no more than a simple rod outfitted with three sets of transparent wings.
The swiftest inhabitants of the Sea of Clouds, cloud cutters will fly straight in a single direction for malms before quickly turning at some unthinkable angle and darting off in another direction.
The blind manta is thought to navigate the Sea of Clouds in a manner similar to how bats keep their bearings─using sound and echoes to determine the location of cliff faces and other creatures.
The rift sailor uses the light elastic webbing between its wings to catch the roiling winds of the Sea of Clouds and glide across the rifts.
When hunting, the Sagolii monkfish uses a method similar to its sea-bound cousin─attracting potential prey to its location with a glowing appendage situated directly above its gaping maw.
Lacking feet or wings to propel itself from the ground, only death awaits the saucerfish that is foolish enough to leave the Sea of Clouds.
After maturing in the Grand Wake, caravan eels will form long lines in the sand and make their way back to the Sagolii Desert to spawn and die.
Its massive lance-shaped nose makes this legendary denizen of the Sea of Clouds a formidable nuisance for airships passing through the area.
A legendary amphibian with a boomerang-like head said to be powerful enough to split a harpoon in two.
A large fish native to the Indigo Deep. When packed in salt, it can be preserved for up to a year.
This medium-sized oyster is high in nutrients, making it optimal for use in medicines and rations.
A giant snail believed to have been bred for consumption during the reign of the Great Allagan Empire.
A giant green toad found in nearly all of the lakes and swamps of Aldenard.
A common, thick-shelled turtle found in wetlands throughout Eorzea.

An amphibious type of scalekin found in the wetlands of Vylbrand. Its body is covered with colorful markings which some of Limsa Lominsa's more superstitious folk believe are burns the creature received when crawling its way through each of the seven hells before arriving on the face of Hydaelyn.
This tiny frog found in the swamps and lakes of the Black Shroud secretes a powerful poison known to induce paralysis.
This giant red toad, native to the swamps of Vylbrand but now found throughout Aldenard, earns its name from the red firerock which once spewed forth from the now-dormant volcano, O'Ghomoro.

A decent-sized piece of rock containing the precious metal electrum.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the precious metal cobalt.

A reddish ore containing large quantities of iron. Its wide availability makes it optimal for smelting in locations where purer forms of iron ore are difficult to procure, such as militia forges. This particular type of kidney ore is far more porous than the common variety, making it much easier to transport.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the precious metal gold.
A colorful ore with a high copper content.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the precious metal platinum.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the metal darksteel.

Very rarely, when consuming the bodies of her victims, the Miser's Mistress will accidentally ingest chunks of mythril ore found lying about the Aurum Vale. The strong acids found within the seedkin's stomach dissolve away impurities, leaving only a near-pure form of the metal.
An extremely hard rock often used in stone weapons and firearms.
A sharp, glossy volcanic stone often used in the manufacture of weapons and jewelry.
A hard variety of obsidian. Said to have been formed in the flames of a wyvern's breath.
A hard yet light variety of obsidian. Said to have been formed in the flames of a dragon's breath.

Use item to acquire the bluebird minion.

His mother was either lost in a terrible hunting accident...or perhaps is just lost.

Use item to acquire the wide-eyed fawn minion.

Use item to acquire the infant imp minion.

It will still be several summers before his trademark whiskers grow out.

Use item to acquire the coeurl kitten minion.

Beware, for if one should cross your path, you will experience seven years of...AWWWWWW.

Only you stand between it and a hard place.

Use item to acquire the gravel golem minion.

Now with 100% less rancor.

Will not carry you to an underwater kingdom if you ride on its back.

Use item to acquire the tiny tortoise minion.

Luckily for you, his teeth haven't all grown in...yet.

Has yet to acquire a taste for blood.

Use item to acquire the gigantpole minion.

Don't ask what he has eaten to grow so plump.

Use item to acquire the buffalo calf minion.

Take care not to suffer 1,000 points of damage...to your heart.

A bitter fruit found growing in the Ixali homelands. While typically avoided by the five races, and even the Ixal themselves, it is a favorite amongst chocobos, and is known to deepen the red hues of their feathers.
A hard, bitter fruit found in the forests of Far Eastern Doma. While typically avoided by the five races, it is a favorite amongst chocobos, and is known to lighten the red hues of their feathers.

A bitter fruit found growing in the arid soils of Mamook. While typically avoided by the five races, and even the Mamool Ja themselves, it is a favorite amongst chocobos, and is known to deepen the green hues of their feathers.
A bitter berry found growing on the distant Isle of Val. While typically avoided by the five races, it is a favorite amongst chocobos, and is known to lighten the green hues of their feathers.

A bitter fruit found growing on the volcanic soil of O'Ghomoro. While typically avoided by the five races, and the kobolds themselves, it is a favorite amongst chocobos, and is known to deepen the blue hues of their feathers.

A bitter fruit found growing on the Cieldalaes─a remote archipelago in the Rhotano Sea. While typically avoided by the five races, it is a favorite amongst chocobos, and is known to lighten the blue hues of their feathers.

A foul, bitter fruit found growing on the Near Eastern island of Thavnair. While typically avoided by the residents of Radz-at-Han, it is a favorite amongst chocobos, and is known to restore feathers to their original hue.
A bitter carrot-like root vegetable native to the Near East. While typically avoided by the five races, it is a favorite amongst chocobos.
A pungent, tear-inducing vegetable that thrives in the alkali sands of Near Eastern Thavnair. While typically avoided by the five races, it is a favorite amongst chocobos.
Pearl roselle seeds suitable for garden cultivation.
Why entrust the sweeping of chocobo dung to a coinless pleb with a sick wife and two starving children when you can toss a bewitched broom into your personal stables and be done?

Seeds suitable for cultivating Mamook pears─a favorite amongst chocobos, and known to deepen the green hues of their feathers.
Seeds suitable for cultivating valfruits─a favorite amongst chocobos, and known to lighten the green hues of their feathers.
Seeds suitable for cultivating O'Ghomoro berries─a favorite amongst chocobos, and known to deepen the blue hues of their feathers.
Seeds suitable for cultivating Cieldalaes pineapples─a favorite amongst chocobos, and known to lighten the blue hues of their feathers.
Seeds suitable for cultivating Han lemons─a favorite amongst chocobos, and known to restore feathers to their original hue.

He believes he can fly. He believes he can touch the sky. Unfortunately he cannot.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Ixal minion.

100% anatomically correct. Handle with care.

Use item to acquire the wind-up succubus minion.

Several arms appear to be missing, but that does not seem to otherwise hinder basic functionality.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Gilgamesh minion.

He would die 4 U. Or possibly cry 4 U. Or most likely make U cry. 4 U.

Use item to acquire the Onion Prince minion.

His childhood dream to become a wizard was frowned upon by his overbearing father.

Use item to acquire the Eggplant Knight minion.

Every breath you take will act as a reminder that your pungent pal is right behind you.

Use item to acquire the Garlic Jester minion.

Has issued a royal decree for the public defenestration of any and all who mistakenly claim the king is a vegetable.

Use item to acquire the Tomato King minion.

Though wed to the Tomato King in a move to strengthen the bond of houses Tomato and Mandragora, the queen longs to steal away with her one true love─the Eggplant Knight. What will become of this forbidden romance!? Use item to acquire the Mandragora Queen minion and find out!

An accurate representation of the soldiers who once made up the greater portion of the Allagan Imperial Army.

Use item to acquire the wind-up onion knight minion.

It is unknown what manner of spirit possesses this tiny treasure chest, but the fact that it will not hesitate to nip at the fingers of any who try and pry it open is painfully evident.

Use item to acquire the treasure box minion.

Natives of the New World claim that tapirs grow by devouring the dreams of their unsuspecting owners. And now you know what to expect.

Use item to acquire the tiny tapir minion.

Pundits claim bears to be the deadliest beasts in the realm. They obviously have never stared into this cute cub's nebulous eyes.

Use item to acquire the Nana bear minion.

Best when ridden in abandoned mines and temples of doom.

Use item to acquire the miniature minecart minion.

That nutkins are infamous for being shy and timid creatures shows that this brave beastkin comes complete with a pair of iron acorns on him.

Use item to acquire the nutkin minion.

Unlike the real Minfilia, this one actually accompanies you on your adventures.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Minfilia minion.

Two hundred percent more dreamy than previous models.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Thancred minion.

Like its parent, the ninki nanka, this slippery wavekin will breed like a rabbit if left unsupervised.

Use item to acquire the naughty nanka minion.

Untrained in arts both martial and magical, but as scrumptiously adorable as chicken glazed in a tangy orange reduction.

Use item to acquire the panda cub minion.

A small hand-carved whistle that emits a unique, high-pitched tone discernible only by a draught chocobo trained from birth to recognize and respond to the sound. Use to summon your personal draught chocobo.
A polished bone horn used to summon an Ixal-trained direwolf.
A hollowed beastkin horn adorned in Maelstrom red that emits a deep bellowing tone which summons your Storm warsteed.
A hollowed beastkin horn adorned in Twin Adder yellow that emits a deep bellowing tone which summons your Serpent warsteed.
A hollowed beastkin horn adorned in Immortal Flames black that emits a deep bellowing tone which summons your Flame warsteed.
This tiny whistle emits a shrill tone which can only be heard by Markab, blessed steed of the Lord of Levin.
A shard of aetheryte which can be attuned to new adventurers, allowing for swift travel to their side in times of need.
A special vintage of sparkling red wine prepared by master vintner Byrglaent of Wineport for the Rising, an annual celebration of Eorzea's rebirth.
This peculiar contraption creates illusions by weaving together myriad shades of light. Produces a radiant light that projects images of the lesser moon Dalamud.
A spinning firework popular in the Far East.
An original creation of the Garlond Ironworks, this handheld device harnesses the power of magitek to emit a sensuous red light.
This particular variety of firework resembles a comet when ignited. Why it is not then called a skycomet, only the Far Eastern inventor who conceived the item knows.
A promissory note that can be exchanged for Ixali oaknots─carved pieces of oak used as currency by the Ixal.

This wristlet signifies a standard agreement between two individuals to form an everlasting spiritual union.
This wristlet signifies a gold-clad agreement between two individuals to form an everlasting spiritual union.
This wristlet signifies a platinum-clad agreement between two individuals to form an everlasting spiritual union.
From this simple ring, a lifelong bond begins.
The Ceremony of Eternal Bonding invitation from which all future invitations are born.
Allows admittance to a Ceremony of Eternal Bonding. Speak with Etoinelle at the Sanctum of the Twelve before using.

There is no better way to tell a special someone “Thank you for attending my Ceremony of Eternal Bonding” than by giving them a sentient box that may or may not devour their pets.

Use item to acquire the demon box minion.

A small hand-carved whistle that emits a unique, high-pitched tone discernible only by a ceremony chocobo trained from birth to recognize and respond to the sound. Use to summon your ceremony chocobo mount.

Though this small baked treat provided by the Continental Circus <Emphasis>appears</Emphasis> to be a cookie, it is difficult to tell what on Hydaelyn it might contain. Consumption should probably be avoided.
Rumor has that fishing enthusiast Biggs used the Garlond Ironworks crafting facilities after-hours to create this magitek-enhanced rod.
A purely decorative chocobo costume created for All Saints' Wake.

Designed to boldly go where you have gone before.

Use item to acquire the model <Emphasis>Enterprise</Emphasis> minion.

For when you absolutely, positively require moogle accompaniment.

Use item to acquire the wind-up delivery moogle minion.

The automaton vehemently refuses to sit upon any shoulder but Raubahn's...and yours.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Nanamo minion.

If we are to take her word for it, the Circle of Knowing Archon has seen but twenty-three summers.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Y'shtola minion.

Comes complete with irremovable mask.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Yda minion.

Comes complete with irremovable smirk.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Papalymo minion.

When the senary moon did wane, there sounded a garrulous and convoluted monologue. A new minion had roused, one whose identity lieth within our ken.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Urianger minion.
This ebon horn emits a somber tone that summons Odin's loyal steed from the elder primal's side to yours.
An expertly crafted replica of the wandering elder primal Odin. (Miniature Sleipnir included.)
An expertly crafted replica of the elder primal Bahamut. (Miniature Nael van Darnus sold separately.)
This plush doll is rumored to be stuffed with countless strips of cloth covered in terrible curses. Slicing open the tonberry to find out what they entail is not recommended.

A commissioned portrait of Scions of the Seventh Dawn leader Minfilia entitled <Emphasis>The Antecedent</Emphasis>. Original artist unknown.

column5: Believed by Eorzean fisherfolk to be the spawn of Thalaos─legendary creator of seas. It is, however, more likely to be no more than an overgrown little Thalaos.
A king among coelacanths.
An ancient sea-dweller with a body like a lance and a temper like the Fury's. Only few have ever seen this living legend, let alone landed one.
A queen among dinichthys.
A king among ignus snails.
A king among Ilsabardian bass.
A champion among boxing plecos.
A king among assassin betta.

A king among morinabaligi.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 4 and higher.]
A legendary white catfish rarely seen by even the eldest of fisherfolk.
A king among titanic saws.
A king among soft-shelled snapping turtles.
A king among vampire lamperns.
A king among wootz knifefish.
A legendary denizen of the sands, the helicoprion's maw is lined with long curved teeth that help it latch onto its airborne prey.
A king among angry pike.
A king among wandering sculpin.
A king among rhamphorhynchus.
Within this legendary scalekin's body can be found a massive secondary bladder containing lighter-than-air gas.
A king among mushroom crabs.

A king among takitaro.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 4 and higher.]
This legendary freshwater fish cares not for those kings or queens who encroach upon his territory, and will turn to regicide to keep his waters his own.

A king among bonytongue.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
A plush chair designed in the south seas style.
An L-shaped couch designed in the south seas style.
A luxurious canopied bed designed in the riviera style.
A luxurious canopied bed designed in the glade style.
A luxurious canopied bed designed in the oasis style.

A broad-leafed perennial common on south seas islands such as the Cieldalaes. The shape of the leaf is said to resemble the ear of a legendary beast twice as tall as a Roegadyn and ten times as heavy.
A simple indoor shower, perfect for cleansing the body and spirit after a long day of adventure.

An impressive objet d'art depicting the head of the dreadwyrm, Bahamut.

※One per estate only.

An expertly crafted representation of the ancient crystalline tower.

※One per estate only.
A quaint round stool designed in the riviera fashion.
A quaint round stool designed in the glade fashion.
A quaint round stool designed in the oasis fashion.

A large wooden wardrobe in which sets of special gear may be stored.

※One per estate only.
A handcrafted stone stove similar to the ones found in the homes of the realm's smallfolk.
A family of four tended their gristmill for a full three turns of the sun to create enough flour to bake this massive tower cake.
A twinklebox without a present is like a child without a smile.
A backless bookshelf designed in the riviera fashion.
A backless bookshelf designed in the glade fashion.
A backless bookshelf designed in the oasis fashion.
A sturdy wooden box once used to import exotics from across the boundless seas.
A wooden barrel once used to mature wine.
A ceramic censer into which aromatic herbs and oils are inserted and then heated to produce a fragrant smoke.
Two stuffed sheep─husband and wife─dressed in traditional Far Eastern garb.
Known in the Far East as “kagami mochi,” these cakes are not traditionally eaten, but displayed before and during Heavensturn.
A handmade doll crafted to resemble a Qiqirn, and dressed in a festive Starlight Celebration outfit.

A whole dodo stuffed with savory vegetables and slow-roasted on a spit. Often prepared near the end of the year as an offering to the Twelve.

※Cannot be retrieved once used.
※Can be used up to 10 times.

A pumpkin-shaped basket filled with All Saints' Wake goodies.

Conceived by Bismarck chefs with far too much time on their hands, the Starlight cake is composed of layer after layer after layer...after layer of sweet, decadent heaven.

※Cannot be retrieved once used.
※Can be used up to 10 times.

A rectangular oil lamp for indoor use.
An extravagant sofa crafted from the rarest wood and finest cloth obtainable; no expense was spared for this Haukke Manor original.
As magnificent as the day it was caught, but without the unpleasant stench of decay.

The sheer size of these jawbones adds credit to rumors that megalodons enjoy feeding on unwary swimmers, and will swallow them whole so as not to saturate the surrounding waters with blood, thereby alerting other nearby predators.
No more half-hearted tales about the one that got away. This legend of this rare, elusive fish will live on in style above your mantle or in your den.

A simple circle of evergreen branches hung on doors during the Starlight Celebration. While the tradition is fairly new, there already exist several theories as to how the practice started. Some believe the circle represents the symbolic beginning and end of a year, and in turn, our lives, while others claim it is merely easier to hang a ring than it is a straight branch.
Without a hanger, where would towels hang?
A semi-complete collection of notices and timetables, warnings and wanted posters, found in Eorzea's many Adventurers' Guilds.
A lawn-green welcome mat designed to complement glade residences.
A welcome mat designed to complement oasis residences.
Try not to wipe your well-traveled feet on this luxurious import.
A deep rectangular box for planting flowers or vegetables.
A small crystal-powered lantern designed in the riviera style used outdoors to light walkways.
A small crystal-powered lantern designed in the glade style used outdoors to light walkways.
A small crystal-powered lantern designed in the oasis style used outdoors to light walkways.
A lamppost of steel such as one might see lining a Gridanian street.
A lamppost of steel such as one might see lining an Ul'dahn street.
A decorated lamppost displayed during All Saints' Wake.

A potted fir, decorated with a star-shaped ornament at its apex.

※Only one Starlight sentinel may be placed in a single estate, regardless of type.

A potted fir, decorated with a crescent moon-shaped ornament at its apex.

※Only one Starlight sentinel may be placed in a single estate, regardless of type.

A potted fir, decorated with a sun-shaped ornament at its apex.

※Only one Starlight sentinel may be placed in a single estate, regardless of type.

Garlean scholars have conducted extensive studies on the subject of why Eorzean snowmen are constructed of only two balls of snow rather than three─the number of choice throughout Ilsabard. The prevailing theory is that extensive studies should not have been conducted on said subject.
A box without a gift is like a bird without a song.
A mini-tower of sliced bamboo and pine branches─the kadomatsu is a Far Eastern oddity traditionally displayed at homes and in temples for the duration of Heavensturn.
Ready your estate for All Saints' Wake with this frightening, yet festive interior wall covering.
This wall bears a festive design certain to bring joy and cheer to all...until you finally get around to taking it down six moons later.
A sturdy wall of locally quarried stones.
A smooth stone floor guaranteed to stay cool in the summer and toe-numbingly cold in the winter.
Give your estate a modern feel with this quality flooring's contemporary pattern.
Hammered steel flooring for those seeking an imperial feel to their residence.
A breathtaking ceiling fixture crafted using tears taken from the Lady of Frost herself.
An awe-inspiring ceiling fixture crafted using tears taken from the Lady of Frost herself and imbued with magicks ancient and forbidden.

An amendment to existing retainer employment contracts allowing for dispatchment on privately owned properties.

※Cottage, house, and mansion gardens can accommodate 1, 2, and 3 retainers, respectively.

A metal stand upon which aetherial wheels are placed and spun to charge. Holds one grade 1 wheel.
※One stand per estate only.
Upon the surface of this multi-aspected crystal are carved the myriad deeds of dark knights from eras past.
Upon the surface of this multi-aspected crystal are carved the myriad deeds of astrologians from eras past.

Legend states that any who drink this mysterious liquid before lying down for the evening will awaken a new man (or woman).

Grants you a single opportunity to edit your retainer's appearance when speaking to a retainer vocate.

A fraction of the size, yet every bit as annoying as the real thing. Be forewarned: once Ultros shows up, he's liable to stick around.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Ultros minion.

Hoary the Snowman was a jolly happy soul, without a pipe, and without a nose, and two eyes made out of something other than coal. Probably slag.

Use item to acquire the Hoary the Snowman minion.

Currently, “baby fat” is the prevailing excuse for this cherubic chick's gigant-like girth.

Use item to acquire the heavy hatchling minion.

Despite convincing research by top academics from around the realm and beyond, most Miqo'te scholars refuse to believe that there may be some ancestral connection between their race and cats (fat or not).

Use item to acquire the fat cat minion.

This particular yeti is content in knowing that bigger is not always necessarily better.

Use item to acquire the Littlefoot minion.

While as cute as a button, remember, mummies are ultimately embalmed corpses damned to eternal thralldom in the land of the living. Have fun.

Use item to acquire the mummy's little mummy minion.

There was an old betta who swallowed a fry. No one knows why it swallowed the fry, but for some reason, the fry can now fly.

Use item to acquire the assassin fry minion.

Legend states these strange creatures can only survive on land as long as the plate atop their heads remains wet.

Use to acquire the water imp minion.

The Seventh Astral Era is secure as long as the Archon is ever at our sides.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Louisoix minion.

As with dark matter, zodium has the faculty to assimilate with other forms of matter, effectively restoring them to their original condition. However, unlike dark matter, which will bond only with certain materials depending on its purity, zodium appears to bond with almost everything, leading one to entertain the notion that this substance mayhap serves as one of the building blocks of all creation.
A sphere scroll designed to act as a receptacle for the soul energy stored within a relic weapon nexus.
A variety of dark matter that possesses light-altering properties. A quick inspection reveals not a single impurity.

Despite the fact this pestle has been carefully crafted to withstand the creation of highly volatile zodium, chances are it will not survive the process.

While some view this traditional Doman gardening technique as naught more than a reflection of man's arrogance in believing nature can be bent to his will, most simply find it a beautiful and calming form of art.
A precision instrument for telling time. Its towering silhouette adds a touch of gravitas to the ambience of any room.
A large bathtub designed in the Doman fashion.
A folding partition commonly found in Far East nations. Upon one side is a reproduction of an ancient Doman wall painting depicting a variety of beastkin in their natural habitat.
A table designed in the Doman fashion. The underside has been treated with strange Eastern magicks to emit heat during the winter months.
While far less nutritious than real vegetables, these wax replicas will look nicer in your pantry.
A counter designed to replicate those found in Adventurers' Guilds across Eorzea. This model comes complete with a built-in light that can be used to illuminate leve plates.
A Hatching-tide-themed floor lamp.

For the denizens of the Twelveswood, the consumption of tea is a means of relaxing the mind, allowing for uninhibited communion with nature.

※Cannot be retrieved once used.
※Can be used up to 10 times.

While for most La Nosceans supper consists of huddling around a fire pit while sopping up a splash of rancid fish stew with a hunk of moldy bread, those who have found their fortune on the seas prefer a multiple-course extravaganza certain to leave even the most wealthy Ul'dahn speechless.

※Can be used up to 10 times.

Considered the most important of the day's seven meals (preceding both pre-midday mead and eleventh bell tarts), the Ul'dahn elite rarely miss this opportunity to gorge themselves before moving on to the next opportunity to gorge themselves.

※Cannot be retrieved once used.
※Can be used up to 10 times.

This pile of parchment appears to be pages taken from <Emphasis>The Last Paean</Emphasis>─a detailed account of the life and times of a legendary bard who traveled the realm bringing joy to all he met. Strewn across one's bureau, the documents give any library or study a heightened air of sophistication.
A miniature wooden altar hung in Doman houses, allowing people to worship the gods within the privacy of their own homes.
Upon this ornamental scroll is painted the Doman character “jin,” meaning “mankind.”
A partition designed in the Doman fashion, reaching to the ceiling and so sturdy that it may as well be a wall.

“If the <Emphasis>man</Emphasis> who once owned the <Emphasis>chest</Emphasis> is now <Emphasis>dead</Emphasis>, he won't mind anyone else using it.” Such was the logic employed when removing this sturdy treasure coffer from Sastasha.
A barrel planter crafted from oak.

A decadent chocolate cake emblazoned with the House Valentione coat of arms.

※Cannot be retrieved once used.
※Can be used up to 10 times.

A luxurious partition designed to resemble those used in the sultana's palace.
A carved wooden podium not unlike the ones used by the Order of Nald'thal to deliver their sermons.

Far more bitter than its black counterpart, green tea is by far the beverage of choice in Far Eastern Doma. To offset the sharpness of its flavor, it is oft accompanied by something sweet, such as sticky rice cakes.

※Can be used up to 10 times.

Have you dreamed of owning your very own well, but are plagued by one or more of the following psychological ailments: acrophobia, claustrophobia, aquaphobia, bathophobia, or cleithrophobia? Well fear no longer. This quality stone well, manufactured in Eorzea with 100% Eorzean materials, requires no hole to be dug, no ground to be sanctified, and no chain letters to be passed along to your dearest enemies.

A striking dummy designed in the Doman fashion.

※Up to three dummies may be placed in a single estate, regardless of type.
A variety of cherry tree from the Far East modified through generations of grafting and crossbreeding to bloom perpetually.
A square sheet of crimson-colored felt upon which dolls are displayed for Little Ladies' Day.
Outdoor lighting certain to heat up any relationship.
A green, leafy tree transplanted from an island in the Cieldalaes. The word “banana” is actually a bastardization of “pamama,” the term used in the fruit's native habitat.
A miniature astroscope used by aspiring astrologians to peer into the farthest reaches of the firmament.
A round outdoor table and matching chairs designed in the riviera fashion.

Though their beady eyes and awkward walk give them an air of unintelligence, dodos are actually quite clever creatures. A mother dodo will, when creating a nest, first dry grass in the sun for several days before adding it to the pile, so as to prevent the growth of molds harmful to her offspring.

A wooden receptacle for use by retainers to store goods entrusted for sale while protecting them from the elements.
※Can only be placed outdoors.

A wooden counter for use by retainers.
※Can only be placed outdoors.
An interior wall bespeckled with a hypnotically random pattern of colorful dots certain to drive any sane man to his wit's end.
An interior wall covered from top to bottom in colorful wavy lines certain to induce seasickness in even the most hardened sailor.
Woven from sweet-smelling rush grass, tatami flooring is the perfect complement to any home furnished in the Doman fashion.
Marble floor tiling alternately colored black and white.
Cobbles commonly used in Ul'dahn roadways and plazas.
Ceiling-mounted lighting expertly crafted to resemble the moon and stars.

One of eight unbelievably high rarity Triple Triad cards.
A small polished whistle carved from thick turtle shell. Emits a low-pitched tone which summons an adamantoise mount to your side.
A gilded horn that, when blown, summons a purebred Abalathian hoarhound mount named after its pack's legendary leader.
A magicked pipe that, when blown, summons the mythical Kirin to your side.
A thin rectangular piece of some unknown material. Placing it near your reprogrammed logistics system will magically bring the machine to life.
A gaudy suit of chocobo armor designed for use during Valentione's Day celebrations.
Chocobo armor designed to replicate the lavish accoutrements of a legendary gambler.

The realm's premier publication on beauty and fashion, this specific copy of <Emphasis>Modern Aesthetics</Emphasis> covers, in detail, techniques on tying the perfect ponytail.

Use to unlock a new hairstyle at the aesthetician.
Redeem for one free play at any of the Manderville Gold Saucer mini attractions (Jumbo Cactpot, Mini Cactpot, chocobo racing, and Triple Triad not included).
A tonic commonly used by Disciples of the Hand to increase focus, allowing for enhanced results when deconstructing complex creations.
A plain white Archon egg believed to bring its bearer good luck as long as it remains uncracked.
