column5: A collection of antique dolls dating back to the Thorne Dynasty. The miniature costumes are in a sorry state, most being moth-eaten and threadbare.
This chest, rumored to have once been stored aboard the <Emphasis>Haar</Emphasis>─the flagship of the dread pirate Mistbeard─appears to have been not-so-gently pried open with a headsman's axe.
Under the proper conditions, this seedling will grow into a tree almost ten fulms high, and produce upwards of four score bananas per season.
When polished, this rare form of limestone closely resembles marble.
While all eggs a basilisk lays contain traces of rare ore, the first egg laid in life is thought to contain the highest concentration, making it highly sought after by potion mixers and alchemists.
While commonly used as bait by fishers across the realm, little worms also make fine chocobo feed, providing a good source of protein for growing birds.
A rare form of earthworm, these fat invertebrates also make fine chocobo feed, providing an excellent source of protein for growing birds.
A savory herb treasured for its ability to enhance focus and concentration.
After gysahl greens, there's no other verdure a race chocobo would rather sink its beak into.
Once found growing all across the island of Mazlaya, this bright-green plant was almost completely wiped out when chocobos brought to the island by farmers devoured nearly every one they could find.
For reasons unknown to you, this crystal has completely lost its elemental charge.
A perfect sphere carved from a petrified tree and polished to enhance its natural luster.
A decorated pair of knives used by mummers in their traveling grotesqueries. The blades have been dulled to prevent injury.
A tiny copper bell commonly affixed to the collars of Ul'dahn lapdogs to inform owners the location of their precious pets.
Carved from a shard of clear fluorite, this lens exhibits higher optical performance than a normal glass lens.
Saurian leather that has been treated with linseed oil to give it a glossy black finish.
An expensive fabric woven from camel hair. Imitations are common, though this piece appears to be legitimate.
This sample of hydrargyrum has been imbued with powerful magicks.

While this broth can be made by simply boiling down the bones of a duck, true culinarians make it a point to brown the bones before adding them to a mixture of savory vegetables and fresh spring water.
A document bearing master crafter Talan's personal seal. Can be presented in exchange for unparalleled mining equipment.
A document bearing master crafter Talan's personal seal. Can be presented in exchange for unparalleled botanist's equipment.
A document bearing master crafter Talan's personal seal. Can be presented in exchange for unparalleled fishing equipment.
Made from the caustic sap of lacquer trees native to the Far East, urushi is used to protect wood by giving it a hard, glossy finish.
A heavy whetstone that appears to be man-made, rather than carved from naturally occurring rock.
Due to its heat-resistant properties, this plaster is oft used to create molds for metalworking.
A rare form of fluorite completely devoid of any interior flaws.
Linseed oil mixed with soot collected from oil lamps to give it a deep-black color.

Thick, brown hair of a Near Eastern monstrosity known as the camel. Dubious reports from sailors claim the beast stands thrice as high as a chocobo, can speak the tongues of man, and has massive humps upon its back which may contain water, wine, or even gold.
A form of cinnabar known to contain traces of quicksilver.

It is an oft-forgotten fact that Frandelont Raimdelle, famed naturalist, father of modern taxonomy, and author of the Raimdelle Codex, tried multiple times (without success) to classify the common duck─most obviously a cloudkin─as a spoken, believing their incessant quackings to be a highly developed language beyond the comprehension of mankind.
Linen cloth treated with magicked oil. When wrapped about ore or metal, it prevents the slow yet gradual diffusion of elemental charge from the material.
Thinly sliced bamboo used to preserve the aroma of rare fragrant wood.
A crystal aspected to both ice and water. House chefs for wealthy and noble families will oft use these rare specimens to chill ales and white wines during the summer moons.
An especially large giant clam. Local fisher estimates put the age of this wavekin at over five score years.
A type of mineral that, when polished, emits an eerie blue glow not unlike the moon while under the influence of Thaliak.
A list of elite marks slain by the log's owner...before the owner herself...fled the battlefield to hunt another day.
One of nine low rarity Triple Triad cards.
One of eight medium rarity Triple Triad cards.
One of nine high rarity Triple Triad cards.
Redeemable for 100 Manderville Gold Saucer points (MGP).

A galette-style pie decorated with a golden crown and served at Ishgardian festivals. Baked using Talan's own special recipe.

Airship-grade refined ceruleum. Required to fuel vessels traveling to the Sea of Clouds on exploratory voyages. Can also be used in submersibles on subaquatic voyages.
A reliable hull used in most Highwind Skyways airships.
A large hull adapted from those used in seafaring galleys.
A hull designed by Cid for use in his personal airship the <Emphasis>Enterprise</Emphasis>.
A modified version of the Invincible-type hull, redesigned to reduce wind resistance.
The reinforced keel of this unique airship is specially tailored to long voyages.
Named after the “father” of propeller-powered airships, the design used in this hull is certain to invoke a sense of inspiring nostalgia.
A simple yet highly durable sheet of thick canvas designed to serve both as a receptacle for lighter-than-air ceruleum gas, as well as a sail to assist propulsion.
Airship lift is achieved by the rapid spinning of ceruleum-powered propellers mounted atop masts placed around the fore and aft decks.
The unique shape of this ceruleum gas bladder directs the flow of air around it, reducing wind resistance.
Speed and flight stability have been increased by adding auxiliary propulsive wings to the ship's masts.
Separate gas regulation control over each bladder allows for increased navigational efficiency.
Taking inspiration from the aether-manipulating flying fish found in the Sea of Clouds, these radical new propellers have been treated with wind-aspected crystals, allowing for increased lift.
The simply crafted front half of a Bronco-type airship, including the main deck and bowsprit.
The sturdily built front half of an Invincible-type airship, including the main deck, bowsprit, and a towering foremast.
The front half of an Enterprise-type airship, including the main deck, bowsprit, and extra lighting to improve nighttime navigation.
The front half of an Invincible II-type airship, including the main deck, bowsprit, and a towering foremast. Wooden parts have been replaced with lightweight metal to improve vessel durability.
The front half of an Odyssey-type airship, including the main deck, bowsprit, an extended hold, and specially designed cooling pipes.
The front half of a Tatanora-type airship, including the main deck, bowsprit, and banks for extra propellers.
The simply crafted rear half of a Bronco-type airship, including the poop deck, ceruleum engine, tiller, and rudder.
The sturdily built rear half of an Invincible-type airship, including the quarter and poop decks, tiller, rudder, ceruleum engine, and two propeller masts.

The rear half of an Enterprise-type airship, including the quarter and poop decks, tiller, rudder, ceruleum engine, and an all-purpose crane for extracting items, or on rare occasions, people in distress.
The rear half of an Invincible II-type airship, including the quarter and poop decks, tiller, rudder, ceruleum engine, and an all-purpose crane equipped with powerful claws.
The rear half of an Odyssey-type airship, including the poop deck, tiller, rudder, and an experimental aetherial propulsion engine.
The rear half of a Tatanora-type airship, including the quarter and poop decks, tiller, rudder, ceruleum engine, and tailplane for improved maneuverability.

A golden-brown jewel consisting of many colored layers. When polished, it resembles the eye of a tiger─a legendary beast believed to be the ancestor of the coeurl.
A cloudy pink jewel consisting of many colored layers.

A green jewel.
A smoky black jewel.
A translucent red jewel. Its relative softness makes it easy to carve, and it has been used by royalty throughout history for signet rings.

The curved canine of a Coerthan yeti. You shudder to think how many throats were ripped open by this nail-like tooth.
The rapier-like fang of an ancient dragon. Some naturalists believe that the age of a dragon can be determined by horizontally slicing its tooth and counting the rings within.
The sharp curved talon of a griffin.

This bark, when boiled down, produces large amounts of tannin─a substance used by leatherworkers to tan hides.
Several yalms of undyed rainbow cloth wrapped around a short wooden distaff.

Strong, absorbent yarn spun from ramie.
Silk gathered from crawler cocoons and spun into a thin lustrous thread.
A rare variety of cotton which produces fibers that change color depending on the angle at which light strikes them.
A variety of swift-growing grass native to the Near East. The stalks can be dried and processed into thin threads which, when spun together, can be woven into a cloth not unlike hemp.
The bristly mane of a biologically engineered monstrosity.
The sticky cocoon of a giant crawler.

This rock-hard scale can withstand the blow of a Roegadyn-wielded battleaxe.
It would take at least twenty tears shed from a heartbroken Lalafellin maiden to equal the liquid volume of one deepeye tear.
The odor of dhalmel saliva has been likened to that of the bloated corpse of a blue cheese artisan drowned in a Grand Company camp latrine and left to sit in the hot sun for a sennight.
Most likely the blood of a dragon. For some unknown reason, the humours will not coagulate.
Clear water taken from a spring in the foothills of Abalathia's Spine.
Clear water taken from a spring on one of the many islets floating above Abalathia's Spine.
Crystal-clear water taken from a secluded spring located on a remote islet floating above the Sea of Clouds.
A rare flower that has an elemental aspect tipped severely in the direction of astral.
A quivering gelatinous lump of voidsent flesh neither cold nor sweet. Consumption is not recommended, even during times of starvation.
The thick leathery wing of a wyvern.
The thin, twitching leaf of an icetrap.
Brought back from the New World in the west, this plant bearing large, horn-shaped flowers has been recently discovered to be effective in curing several different ailments.
This sweet-smelling perennial can be found growing in all of the Three Great Continents.

This common flower produces a globe of lightweight seeds that are carried remarkable distances when blown in the wind. While the stalk is filled with a toxic milky substance, the leaves and roots can be dried and brewed into medicinal infusions.

A relative to pepper- and spearmint, gaelicatnip is an aromatic herb often brewed into teas. While it has no effect on the five races, the oil contained in the leaves is known to cause gaelicats and other normally aggressive feline beastkin to exhibit excessively playful behavior.
A low-growing shrub recognizable by its tiny yellow flowers and faint odor. The leaves contain a mild irritant that, when rubbed against the skin, may cause minor reddening and swelling.
A highly fragrant herb. The leaves can be harvested and used in salads, or the plant can be allowed to bolt and the seeds gathered and used to spice ale.

This small music box cylinder is studded with myriad pins arranged in a queer pattern. When placed in a music box and attached to the motor, the cylinder will rotate, causing the pins to strike the box's comb, creating music.
This leather has been tanned and treated using techniques from the Near Eastern island of Thavnair.
This silk has been spun from thread created by a worm found only on the Near Eastern island of Thavnair.
A small piece of throbbing flesh sliced from the devourer of worlds, Atomos.
A coiled ribbon of steel commonly used in clockwork creations to perpetuate motion.
Several steel balls set into a polished metal ring. It is used to reduce friction, allowing a wheel to spin with little resistance.
Its name meaning “wolf,” the lupin is a hardy plant resistant to the cold winds of the Eorzean north.
A jagged sheet of plating fallen from the armor of an iron giant.
Protective metal plating used in the fabrication of a magitek gobwalker G-VII.
An oblong coin of gold commonly used in the Far East for bribes.
A detailed design document outlining the absurdly complex steps required to craft a toy box.
A yellowish mineral used by leatherworkers to tan animal hides. This particular variety exhibits some of the best deodorizing properties of all alumen.
The seedling of a squat shrub favored by topiarists across the realm for its bright-green leaves and dense web of tiny branches.
A gaudy moogle-sized crown crafted by moogles for use during moogle celebrations.
An especially dark variety of leather often used in formalwear and uniforms.

A detailed outline of complex woodworking techniques. One delineation is consumed when using the <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Heart of the Carpenter<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> specialist action.

This comprehensive manual, written by a disgruntled former employee of Rowena's House of Splendors, provides a detailed explanation of inhuman techniques forced upon consortium-hired Disciples of the Hand to increase their output. It is known to inspire (and frighten) all who read it, granting a temporary 150% boost to experience points earned from synthesis (up to a maximum of 300,000 points). Effect is halved at level 70 and above.

A striking dummy designed in the Sharlayan fashion.

The stalks of these bright-yellow flowers have been known to grow to heights of two or three yalms.

※Up to ten flower plots may be placed in a single garden, regardless of type.
This wooden idol carved in the likeness of the primal Bismarck is used by Vanu Vanu priests during summoning ceremonies.
This steel idol resembling the primal Ravana is used by the Gnath during summoning ceremonies.

column5: Stonefly nymphs are constantly moving, making them easily discernible targets for poor-sighted fish. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
This lightweight spider can distribute its weight over a large surface area, allowing it to “walk” on water without sinking. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
A metal lure designed by goblin fishers to vibrate rapidly, thus making it more appealing to hungry fish.
An all-purpose fishing lure crafted by combining three smaller lures.

A bright-red breed of balloon bug found floating at higher elevations than its duller cousins. Live bait for both skyfishing and cloudfishing. Up to nine hundred and ninety-nine red balloons can be stacked together.
A small worm with a stone-like shell encasing its entire body, protecting it from the extreme temperatures of the molten lava in which it resides. Live bait for hellfishing.

Discovered almost simultaneously by three naturalists, this strange creature was also named the “demon worm” and the “goddess worm” until a best-two-out-of-three round of stone-parchment-shears settled the naming problem once and for all. Fiend worms are one of the few baits suitable for aetherfishing, as the vilekin will remain alive in the sludge even when submerged.
A fat bloodsucking worm often found attached to large fish or the legs of wading fauna. Live bait for freshwater fishing.
A mosquito-like vilekin with uncharacteristically long legs. Often utilized by anglers for both cloud and skyfishing.
A freshwater fish adapted to survive in the cold waters of Coerthas. It earns its name from its long, beak-like mouth.
A white lightweight coral found growing on the floating islands above Eorzea.
A tiny “winged” slug commonly found in ice-ridden freshwater lakes.
A wingless worm that has somehow learned to fly.
A freshwater crustacean only found in the coldest of lakes.
When closed, the shells of this freshwater bivalve mollusk form a demonic rictus that will haunt your nightmares until the end of time. Possibly beyond.
A freshwater urchin which survives by eating the sparse algal blooms in Twinpools.

A small, red catfish native to the Whilom River.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
A freshwater shrimp native to the Whilom River.
A flower-like mollusk found floating about the Sea of Clouds.
A spherical creature found flying in the icy northern reaches of the Sea of Clouds bordering the Coerthas western highlands.
A freshwater mollusk with a twisted shell shaped like the horn of a voidsent ogre. Can only survive in warm temperatures, such as those found in hot springs.
A freshwater fish believed by some to have the ability to wield Fire spells.
A freshwater fish native to the freshwater runoff of Abalathia's Spine. It is easily distinguishable by its long, ever-twitching whiskers.
A thin freshwater fish commonly found in the floating lakes above Abalathia.
A large freshwater fish covered in gil-sized silver scales.
A stout, deep-voiced wavekin found throughout Abalathia's Spine.
A semi-transparent freshwater fish native to the lakes of legendary Voor Sian Siran.
A cloud white mollusk found living on the underbelly of Abalathia's floating islets.
A tiny freshwater bivalve mollusk native to the lukewarm waters of the Whilom River in the Dravanian forelands.
The expression “when eggs fly” was commonly used throughout Eorzea to express the impossibility of something...that is until the discovery of this strange creature floating about the Sea of Clouds.
A mushroom/loom-like flying fish native to the Sea of Clouds.
A blue lightweight coral found growing on the floating islands above Eorzea.
A fatty freshwater fish native to Twinpools.
A giant cephalopod characterized by its spectacular dual-walled whorling shell.

A freshwater fish found only in the pools and lakes of Abalathia's floating islets.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]
A freshwater fish native to the Hundred Throes, where it conceals itself in the churning waters of the myriad cataracts.

A deadly freshwater fish which will tear away flesh with its razor-sharp teeth. Crossing the Whilom River barefoot is not recommended.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

A peculiar breed of freshwater catfish that swims upside down. It was first discovered in Weston Waters.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]

An adorable freshwater fish native to the waters of Eil Tohm.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
A flying slug native to the Sea of Clouds.
This hard-shelled crustacean is one of few creatures on Eorzea which withstand the heat of molten lava.
A spherical creature found in the upper atmospheric region of the Sea of Clouds.
A freshwater fish named after Thaliak, the Scholar.
A massive freshwater fish who lurks beneath the thick sheet of ice covering Ashpool.

A freshwater fish inhabiting the Eddies─an isolated lake found atop one of Abalathia's floating islets.

A variety of pliable rubber imbued with arcane magicks to improve aetherial conductivity.
Born of Allagan ingenuity, this aetherochemical concoction is said to rapidly increase a gem's hardness.
Water believed to be blessed by the Twelve. Used to exorcise powerful demons from worldly items.

Dubbed a “god in the machina” by those who first discovered it, modern scholars have yet to discover not only what the catalytic agent contains, but exactly how it functions, understanding only that the substance is required to quickly strengthen the properties of certain materials.
An expertly crafted bolt discovered in Alexander's Gordias sector.
This highly collectable bone appears to be from a creature not recorded in the Raimdelle Codex.
An expertly crafted lens discovered in Alexander's Gordias sector.
This highly collectable shell appears to be from a creature not recorded in the Raimdelle Codex.
An expertly crafted spring discovered in Alexander's Gordias sector.
This highly collectable variety of ore is undocumented in the extensive Amajina & Sons mining logs.
An expertly crafted shaft discovered in Alexander's Gordias sector.
These highly collectable seeds appear to be from flora not recorded in the Raimdelle Codex.
A small throwing axe forged from adamantite.
A thin leather strap cut from the cured hide of a pterodactyl.
The reflective surface on this mirror has been achieved through countless days of buffing and polishing.
A thin, tiny plate of hammered titanium alloy.
Not actually an arrow, but rather a warding charm carved into the shape of one.
Arrow fletchings crafted from the large, rigid feathers of an eagle and then blessed by an anointed Halonic priest.
A festive ring-shaped cake baked from brioche dough.
A small ceramic figurine bearing the likeness of a plump moogle.
A list of elite marks slain by the log's owner...before the owner himself vanished without a trace following an embarrassing defeat at the hands of a ladybug.
A small coin of low denomination once used in the long-fallen nation of Mhach. Actively sought by numismatists across Eorzea.
A small piece of steel salvaged from a helm worn by one of the Heavens' Ward.

When sky pirates raiding in the Sea of Clouds board another vessel, it is tradition to claim a piece of the airship to serve as proof of the deadly deed. These objects of honor and bravery have also been known to be used as currency between the brigands.

A promissory note that can be exchanged for Vanu whitebones─tiny, bleached bones used as common currency amongst the many Vanu Vanu tribes.
A promissory note that can be exchanged for sylphic goldleaves─golden, decaying leaves used as currency by the sylphs.
A promissory note that can be exchanged for steel Amalj'ok─small, curved steel blades used as currency by the Amalj'aa.
A promissory note that can be exchanged for rainbowtide psashp─colorful shells used as currency by the Sahagin.
A promissory note that can be exchanged for Titan cobaltpieces─crude pieces of flattened cobalt used as high denomination currency by the kobolds of O'Ghomoro.
This spiritous concoction instantly restores a considerable amount of HP.
Processed via the alchemical extraction of aetheric essence occurring in elemental crystals, the contents of this vial instantly restore a considerable amount of MP.

There is much debate amongst Eorzean scholars as to how much time must pass before a bone becomes fossilized. Some say a mere generation will suffice, citing evidence such as the proliferation of petrification magicks. Others believe it may take upwards of a thousand thousand years, casting doubts on the theories which state Hydaelyn was created a mere twenty thousand summers past.

A note of promise received from Rowena for the delivery of Allagan tomestones of lore or poetics.
Ironworks experts insist these tomestones not only contain reams of invaluable information from the Allagan Empire, but compress a far greater wealth of knowledge within than the average tomestone.
This ligneous idol resembling the primal Sephirot is said to have been used by a tribe of treelike beings during summoning ceremonies.

Two lenses can be traded for special headgear.

column5: Similar to the more common tomestones believed to store the lost knowledge of the Allagan Empire, yet at the fraction of the size, micro tomestones are highly sought by collectors and scholars alike.

An alchemical potion concocted in the dark laboratoriums of the Illuminati. Some of Idyllshire's goblin goldsmiths have applied the unnaturally viscous substance to a variety of precious stones and found that it heightens the attributes of the gear and accessories crafted in their workshops.

An alchemical thread woven in the dark laboratoriums of the Illuminati. Some of Idyllshire's goblin weavers have applied the unnaturally pliable substance to a variety of vestments and found that it heightens the attributes of gear woven in their looms.

An alchemical potion concocted in the dark laboratoriums of the Illuminati. Some of Idyllshire's goblin smithies have applied the unnaturally illuminated substance to a variety of metals and found that it heightens the attributes of weapons crafted in their forges.

Two lenses can be traded for special headgear.

An ingot of smelted wolfram alloy.
An ingot of smelted luminium ore.
Tufted fabric with extremely short pile rendering it smooth to the touch. This rare velvet's thin fibers grant it a unique glossiness from which it earns its name.
A large piece of cured hemicyon hide.

A decadently creamy concoction crafted from raw eggs, thick cream, honey, and─if you are feeling adventurous─a healthy splash of a dark spiced rum. A favorite in Ishgard's Vault.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m

A rare variety of cotton which produces nitid fibers that, when struck by light, coruscate like the very stars in the heavens.
An earthen fungus that can commonly be found sprouting beneath trees growing in the Churning Mists.
A fragrant herb used in medicines, perfumes, and cooking. Its deep blue flowers set it apart from its cousin, clary sage.
A bright-yellow mineral formed by the weathering of scheelite.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the precious metal luminium.
A porous silicate that adsorbs poisons, making it invaluable in myriad alchemical and medical concoctions.
Titanium that has been ground to a powder and carbonized via extreme heat.
A small nugget of impure luminium.
Silk so thin, it is barely discernable with the naked eye, despite proving as tensile as normal silken thread. Only silkworms bred under strict conditions will produce such fiber.
The thick bristly hide of an ancient breed of canine believed unchanged for seven Astral Eras.
A protective sealant created by goblins and used to protect wood from rot and water damage, as well as provide it a lustrous sheen.
A potent solvent created by goblins and known for its biting odor said to resemble unrefined ceruleum.
Aetherial residue seeped forth from spiritbound weapons.

column5: Oft employed by sky pirates and other unsavory individuals to protect their hard-earned plunder, these small containers are nigh impossible to open by all but the most skilled lockpicks.

This lockbox is so badly damaged that the chances whatever lies within remains undamaged are slim. Most lockpicks (who oft claim as part of their fee a certain portion of a box's contents) will not even attempt to open one. Bring them several, however, and they may be more amenable to the task.

Currency once used on the Near Eastern island of Thavnair, now only sought by numismatists and historians.
Ice stalactites <Emphasis>hold on tight</Emphasis> to the ceiling of a cave. This is not an ice stalactite.
Infusions made with this hardy brown-black foliage are believed to restore vigor.
A small bead of naturally formed glass that could pass off as an eye, if viewed from thirty paces...in the fog.
Extracted from natural sources, this colorful powder can be prepared to create an equally colorful dye.
A freshwater fish originally native to the Near Eastern island of Thavnair. How they ultimately ended up in the upper Thaliak River remains an enigma.
An almost entirely transparent shell-less mollusk found solely in the waters of Clearpool.
A blood red species of coral found growing on the undersides of islands in the Sea of Clouds.
A tiny pinkish bivalve mollusk found primarily in Weston Waters.

Little is known about this deceptively heavy substance save that its origins lie not in this world.
Sturdy cloth woven with two varieties of thread─wool and cotton.
Because who hasn't dreamed of hugging a cactus?

Most often found in markets located across the eastern and southern regions of Eorzea, this lightly glazed buttery brioche pastry will keep for several days (making it a fine companion for long journeys), but is best when freshly baked. Guaranteed to make life sweeter.

A small coin of low denomination once used in the long-fallen nation of Mhach. Actively sought by numismatists across Eorzea. There are twelve Mhachi pennies in a shilling.

This esoteric tome─the fifth in an equally esoteric series─contains advanced smithing recipes that can only be learned by esoterically skilled blacksmiths.

This esoteric tome─the fifth in an equally esoteric series─contains advanced goldsmithing recipes that can only be learned by esoterically skilled goldsmiths.

This esoteric tome─the fifth in an equally esoteric series─contains advanced clothcraft recipes that can only be learned by esoterically skilled weavers.

All the materials necessary to construct an oriental dressing case. (Crystal not included.)
A dressing case of oriental design, featuring a large mirror of polished metal and countless compartments for jewelry and sundry maquillage.
All the materials necessary to construct an oriental pipe box. (Crystal not included.)
A pipe box of oriental design, complete with an ashtray and compartments for several varieties of tobacco.
All the materials necessary to construct an authentic Doman partition. (Crystal not included.)
An exquisitely crafted partition of traditional Doman design.
All the materials necessary to construct a folding bench traditionally used in the Far East. (Crystal not included.)
A folding bench commonly found in Far Eastern teahouses, complete with a paper parasol to shield tea-drinkers from the elements.
All the materials necessary to forge a shortsword. (Crystal not included.)
A sword so lightweight, even the elder steward Fremondain can wield it with relative ease.
Pieces of iron so rusted it is difficult to discern their former use.
A katana forged to be, above all else, durable.
An ingot forged in the hell-hot furnaces of Limsa Lominsa's Blacksmiths' Guild.
A remarkably small hammer intended for use on projects requiring extreme delicacy.
All the materials necessary to forge a proper uchigatana. (Crystal not included.)
A katana forged as your final test, and to be delivered to a prominent noble house.
All the materials necessary to forge a suit of titanium plate mail. (Crystal not included.)
A titanium-alloy breastplate fit for a paladin.
All the materials necessary to forge a pair of Far Eastern gauntlets known as “kote.” (Crystal not included.)
Lightweight gauntlets of Far Eastern design, forged with titanium for added durability.
All the materials necessary to forge a Far Eastern helm known as a “somen.” (Crystal not included.)
Lightweight headgear of Far Eastern design. For use in Hingan tournaments known as “gozen-jiai.”
All the materials necessary to forge a Far Eastern breastplate known as a “hara-ate.” (Crystal not included.)
A breastplate that combines Hingan design with Lominsan craftsmanship, bringing east and west together at last.
All the materials necessary to forge a silver ring. (Crystal not included.)
A silver ring set with a single brilliant lapis lazuli recovered from the crown of Nanamo Ul Namo's mother.
All the materials necessary to craft a pair of spectacles. (Crystal not included.)
A pair of corrective glasses crafted to accommodate for J'khebica's failing eyesight.
All the materials necessary to craft a desktop chronometer. (Crystal not included.)
A small desktop chronometer to be employed in the training of apprentices.
All the materials necessary to craft a fully operational orchestrion. (Crystal not included.)
An elegant and compact orchestrion custom-made by the Crown Gemworks as a tribute for the sultana.
The smooth hide of a towering dhalmel found only in Hengr's Crucible.
A dhalmel hide expertly trimmed and prepared for stuffing.
The bristly hide of a ferocious Velodyna grizzly bear. The countless holes attest to difficulty in bringing down the beast.
A thick pair of protective gloves crafted from the tanned hide of a grizzly bear.
All the materials necessary to craft a stylish dhalmelskin jacket. (Crystal not included.)
Sophisticated outerwear for the discerning gentleman <Emphasis>or</Emphasis> woman.
The luxurious skin of an exotic gagana.
A gagana hide expertly trimmed and prepared for stuffing.
All the materials necessary to sew an Ishgardian bustle dress. (Crystal not included.)
A bustle dress of Ishgardian design, featuring extra hoops and springs to prevent unsightly sagging.
All the materials necessary to sew a spring dress. (Crystal not included.)
A beautiful dress crafted with only the finest materials.
All the materials necessary to sew a figure-enhancing bustier. (Crystal not included.)
A bustier of Thavnairian design, cut low to distract potential business clients, thus providing the upper hand in negotiations.
All the materials necessary to sew a Far Eastern robe known as a “hagoromo.” (Crystal not included.)
A billowy kimono of Far Eastern design named for angelic beings from Hingan folklore.
All the ingredients necessary to brew a potent performance-enhancing tonic. (Crystal not included.)
A sweetened tonic believed to improve cognition.
All the ingredients necessary to brew a mean beverage. (Crystal not included.)
Fermenting Mun-Tuy extract twice greatly lessens the beans' natural bitterness, resulting in a smoother aftertaste. Side effects of the beverage include a decided loosening of the tongue.
All the ingredients necessary to concoct a batch of blood-detecting luminol. (Crystal not included.)
When applied to an object that has recently been in contact with blood, this alchemical admixture will change color.
All the ingredients necessary to concoct a batch of highly acidic dissolvent. (Crystal not included.)
Dissolvent so potent it will eat through almost anything.
All the ingredients necessary to cook a rice ball─the Far Eastern treat. (Crystal not included.)
Simple triangular balls of steamed sticky rice sprinkled with naught but a pinch of sea salt so that one might appreciate the subtle flavors of the original ingredients.
All the ingredients necessary to brew a simple fish stock─one of the pillars of Far Eastern cuisine. (Crystal not included.)
Golden savory stock taken by boiling flakes of a dried bonito. Used in many varieties of Far Eastern cuisine, including the noodle dish, udon.
All the ingredients necessary to create the traditional Far Eastern specialty─sushi. (Crystal not included.)

One of many types of sushi, nigiri-zushi is called such because chefs use their hands to grip (nigiri) and form small balls of vinegared rice onto which are placed various items such as vegetables or fish.
All the ingredients necessary to create the (supposedly) traditional Far Eastern specialty─sukiyaki. (Crystal not included.)
Originally introduced to Doma by Ala Mhigan merchants, sukiyaki is a popular dish that consists of thinly sliced meat and vegetables cooked in sweet and savory soy-based sauce.
Lower aetherial conductivity than regular mythril makes this a poor substitute for the precious green metal...unless low aetherial conductivity is what you require.
Not technically as light as an actual feather, this rare variety of iron weighs slightly less than normal iron, making it a preferable alternative...if enough can be procured.
This rare mineral, also known as lizardite, is still believed in some regions to be the lithified remains of a great scalekin.
This oddly named ore was dubbed such by early Gyr Abanian settlers who believed the chunks of colorful mineral to be pieces of a larger rock shattered by a single blow of the Destroyer's fist.
Allowed to grow unchecked in the wild, it only took a matter of generations for this transplant from the New World to become decidedly different than its farm-grown cousins.
A variety of popoto bred by a botanist named Walker to withstand the harsh winds and rocky soil of southern La Noscea.
This light brown seaweed with spiked “leaves” is quite common in the seas off Hingashi, and collected and dried for use in cuisine.
Also known as Rhalgr's staff, this long-leafed medicinal herb is native to the highlands of Gyr Abania.
This variety of Velodyna carp is not named for the deep river pools in which it hides from predators, but the dark coloring of its skin.
A newly hatched fry of the brilliantly red harutsuge.
Rumored to be immortal by local villagers, this freshwater fish native to Yanxia is easily discernable by its countless facial “whiskers.”
Few scholars will disagree that this enormous scalekin sits atop the oceanic food chain.
This quaint pallet will never <Emphasis>betray you</Emphasis> a good night's sleep.

All the music from your world, all in the palm of your...table.

※One orchestrion of any type per estate only.
Is your table cluttered with ashtrays, deathmouse pelts, or forbidden tomes, leaving little to no room to display those beautiful begonias? This wall-adorning vase would like a word with you.
One of the tallest beastkin known on Eorzea, the dhalmel is almost as majestic in your living room as it is in the wild. Almost.
A majestic gagana, gutted, tanned, and stuffed, so as not to wrinkle the noses of your houseguests.
A pipe box of Far Eastern design, complete with an ashtray and compartments for several varieties of tobacco.
A dressing case of Far Eastern design, featuring a large mirror of polished metal and countless compartments for jewelry and sundry maquillage.
A partition of traditional Doman design for use in both homes and places of business.

A statuette depicting the Lady of Bliss, Lakshmi. (Qalyana chieftainess unsurprisingly missing.)

※One per estate only.

A statuette depicting the Lord of the Revel, Susano. (Legendary blade Ame-no-Murakumo included. Second “O” missing, and nowhere to be found.)

※One per estate only.
A trophy awarded to those who “left their mark” in Season Five of the Feast.
Go ahead. Try and convince yourself that the reason this stuffed doll weighs considerably more than similar toys is because her heart is full to bursting with love.
The bladder of some poor beast, colored with dye and filled with lighter-than-air gas to dazzle the young <Emphasis>and</Emphasis> the young at heart come the Rising.

An exotic Far Eastern dish of sweet, vinegared rice, raw fish, and marine flora prepared to stimulate not only the tongue, but the eyes.

※Cannot be retrieved once used.
※Can be used up to 10 times.

A three-legged wooden frame upon which a painting may be placed to cozen your kith and kin into believing you were responsible for the masterpiece.
An empty glass receptacle that dreams of being full once more.
A thin square pillow common in Hingashi where denizens of the Far Eastern nation prefer to sit upon the floor than employ chairs.
An unadorned partition, reaching only less than halfway to the ceiling so as to provide privacy without making the room feel smaller.
A faithful depiction of summer's hottest festival so that you may feel the heat year-round.

Thinly shaved ice, generously heaped into an oversmall bowl and drizzled with sweet yet tangy rolanberry syrup. Why it never melts is a question best served cold.

This charming knickknack is designed after the maneki neko, a Far Eastern cat fetish whose uplifted paw is believed to beckon fortune to its owner's establishment.
Much like the maneki neko (or moogle, for that matter), the Matanga lamp is also believed to bring fortune to any and all who might place them inside their homes.
A tiny rendition of the already tiny Khloe Aliapoh, seeker of a thousand tales.
In the Far East, foxes are believed to be the most cunning of thieves. And once you find your heart missing, you will be a believer, too.

A slightly suggestive objet d'art that will ever remind you of your dominance over the mythic steed.

※One per estate only.
A surprisingly old pine tree, meticulously trimmed for years by trained botanists to remain relatively small, yet maintain the air of a lofty sentinel.
A wooden folding bench and accompanying papercraft umbrella similar to those found at Hingan teahouses.
A specially bred shrub pruned to the shape of a curious Carbuncle.
A giant stone head carved to resemble drawings found in an unknown sailor's diary that one day washed up on the eastern shores of Othard.
A brightly dyed banner bearing the ancestral mark of the Dataq tribe.

A striking dummy designed in the Gyr Abanian fashion.

※Up to three dummies may be placed in a single estate, regardless of type.

column5: An alchemical potion concocted by mad scientists a thousand years dead. Some of the realm's more daring blacksmiths have applied the unnaturally viscous substance to a variety of weapons and found that it heightens the attributes of certain martial artifacts of ancient Allagan design.

An alchemical thread woven by mad scientists a thousand years dead. Some of the realm's more daring weavers have applied the unnaturally pliable substance to a variety of vestments and found that it heightens the attributes of certain martial artifacts of ancient Allagan design.

An alchemical potion concocted by mad scientists a thousand years dead. Some of the realm's more daring goldsmiths have applied the unnaturally illuminated substance to a variety of gems and found that it heightens the attributes of certain martial artifacts of ancient Allagan design.
A note of promise received from Rowena for the delivery of Allagan tomestones of creation or poetics.

Though considerably different in construction, Garlond Ironworks engineers insist this bulky contraption serves the same purpose as a traditional tomestone, and is merely of an earlier, less efficient design.
The Kojin carve, from shell, idols such as this one to present as offerings to their exalted Lord of the Revel, Susano.
This pulsating metal idol forged in the likeness of the primal Lakshmi is thought to be employed by the Ananta in forbidden summoning ceremonies.

A uniquely crafted lens discovered in the Deltascape.

Two lenses can be traded for special headgear.

A uniquely crafted shaft discovered in the Deltascape.

Four shafts can be traded for special body gear.

A uniquely crafted crank discovered in the Deltascape.

Two cranks can be traded for special arm gear.

A uniquely crafted spring discovered in the Deltascape.

Four springs can be traded for special leg gear.

A uniquely crafted pedal discovered in the Deltascape.

Two pedals can be traded for special foot gear.

A uniquely crafted chain discovered in the Deltascape.

One chain can be traded for a special belt.

A uniquely crafted bolt discovered in the Deltascape.

One bolt can be traded for a special accessory.

Detailed records of past battles waged in the Deltascape.

Logs of the same type can be traded for special gear.

Detailed records of past battles waged in the Deltascape.

Logs of the same type can be traded for special gear or materials.

Detailed records of past battles waged in the Deltascape.

Logs of the same type can be traded for special gear or materials.

Detailed records of past battles waged in the Deltascape.

Logs of the same type can be traded for special gear.
A remarkable crystalline fragment within which can be seen images from another world.
The blade from a sword used by the Lord of the Revel himself. Despite being long removed from its hilt, the steel still shudders with unseen magicks.
A long sheet of translucent cloth taken from the robes worn by the Lady of the Bliss. In addition with being unnaturally lightweight, the shroud tingles the skin when touched.

Heather charr sprinkled with salt and blackened over an open flame.

Stiff tofu squares and vegetables impaled on a stick and slathered in a sweet miso sauce then roasted over hot coals.

A Near Eastern casserole made from a spiced jhammel and eggplant mincemeat topped with creamy mashed popotoes.

A hodgepodge of boldly sliced tubers, mushrooms, and hornbill tenders, stewed slowly in a soy-based broth.

A salad of various seasonal tubers tossed lightly in a rice vinegar dressing.

(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)

Rich, buttery crab legs blended with fluffy mashed vegetables, rolled into a ball, covered in bread crumbs, and fried to a crispy, golden-brown. Best served slathered in a sweet sauce.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m

column2: bowl of miso soup with tofu
column3: bowls of miso soup with tofu
column5:
A Far Eastern staple, often eaten multiple times a day, this soup is made by mixing miso paste with light fish stock. Bite-sized cubes of tofu are added near the end of preparation to ensure the pieces retain their shape.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m

A salty broth containing balls of finely ground fish paste. A common dish in Far Eastern coastal settlements.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m

This Far Eastern take on a campsite mainstay features thinly sliced pork belly and various root vegetables in a piping hot miso-based soup.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m

A simple stew commonly made of diced dzo chuck and whatever vegetables are readily available. A popular dish amongst the nomadic tribes of the Azim Steppe.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m

Buckwheat kernels boiled in bullion to form a soft hearty porridge.

Ground dzo chuck and various steppe vegetables wrapped in buttery dough and deep-fried in oil.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)

The fermenting of tea leaves is common practice in the Far East where tea is consumed multiple times a day. Fermentation is thought to enhance flavor while dulling the leaves' natural bitterness. Fermented leaves are pressed into bricks to save space when shipping.
Finely milled Gyr Abanian wheat.
A traditional source of protein in the Far East, tofu is made from curdled soy bean extract.
One of Far Eastern cuisine's five main seasonings, rice vinegar is slightly more sweet and mild than Aldenard's vinegars of popoto or apple.
A sweetener made by juicing sugar beets and then boiling the extract down until all the water has evaporated, leaving only a fine, grey powder.
Far Eastern rice wine prepared with other ingredients for use in cooking. Often added to seafood dishes to remove unpleasant aromas.
Cooking oil pressed from ruby cotton seeds. Its high flash point and lack of odor make it ideal for deep-frying.
A coagulant naturally found in seawater, commonly used in the Far East to make tofu.
A briny salt harvested by sun-drying then burning sea algae.
Unlike the drier varieties common in Aldenard and Ilsabard, this particular strand of Far Eastern rice becomes extremely sticky when cooked.
A nutty grain that can be substituted for flour in breads and noodles. Found across the Three Great Continents, but grown in abundance in the heart of Gyr Abania.

A sweet yet slightly tangy fruit with a thin skin and a fleshy orange interior. Can be found in the warmer valleys of Gyr Abania.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)

A greenish-pink plum common across the eastern continent of Othard.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)

The root of the quick-growing kudzu vine is dug up and processed into kudzu powder which serves as a substitute for animal-based gelatins in Far Eastern desserts. It also is believed to exhibit healing properties, and can be found in most Hingan and Doman apothecaries.
While just as brilliantly purple, this Far Eastern cousin of the wizard eggplant is noticeably thinner, and thus requires less time to cook.
The spicy daikon radishes of Othard are known to grow as long and thick as a grown Hyur's forearm.
These tubers can be several times sweeter than most fruit, and as such are commonly processed into sugar for sweetening cakes and other confections.

Jhammel ginger's bulbous, aromatic roots can be sliced fresh and added to stews and seafood dishes to remove gaminess, ground and steeped in hot water to cure head colds, or dried and ground into a powder to use as a spice for breads and cookies.
Gyr Abanian carrots are not only longer, but a far deeper orange─nay, crimson─than those grown in central and western Eorzea.
Similar to green onions in flavor, the leeks of Gyr Abania are several times thicker, and far more piquant.
If removed from the ground when less than a fulm in length, bamboo shoots can be peeled and the fleshy interior eaten. A popular ingredient in Far Eastern stews and stir-fries.
Crisp mountain popotoes contain high quantities of starch that create a viscous paste when the tubers are ground. This paste can be eaten raw, fried into cakes, or added to stews for thickening.

These emerald legumes grow two to three beans per pod on stout bushes that are ready for harvest in the early fall. The beans are most often pressed into the milk which is used to make tofu, or fermented into various savory pastes and sauces.
These fungi native to the Far East are rarely eaten raw, the majority of those harvested dried, then used to make soup stock.
A pungent spice that can be used in seed form, or ground into a powder, enhancing the aroma tenfold.
Though they appear solid from the outside, the cylindrical root nodules of the lotus flower are riddled with holes, possibly to accommodate for the waterlogged environments in which the plant grows.
The sweet, tightly packed leaves of Othardian sun cabbages are deceptively sweet, making them perfect in salads or stews.
With an aroma similar to licorice, both the stalks and the seeds of this Othardian herb can be used to enhance the flavor of exotic Far Eastern dishes.
A close cousin to highland wheat, Gyr Abanian wheat has been improved by Ala Mhigan farmers over generations to increase both flavor and yield.

A hard, orange fruit common in eastern Othard. It is well known that seven summers must pass before a newly planted persimmon tree will bear fruit.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
While not edible, the leaves of the persimmon tree are oft used in the preservation of other food.

column2: bottle of Gyr Abanian mineral water
column3: bottles of Gyr Abanian mineral water
column5: Clear water taken from a mountain spring on the eastern end of Abalathia's Spine.
Clear, odorless water taken from one of the many springs found on Othard's Fanged Crescent.
The unbearably tough shoulder meat of a steppe dzo.
A lean piece of meat taken from under the short ribs of an Othardian hornbill.
Heavy salting and spicing are methods commonly employed to remove the oft overpowering gaminess of this beastkin flesh.
A dark-haired variety of swine bred on Hingashi's Koshu island. Its carefully selected diet is believed to render its meat tender and its fat flavorful.
The massive egg of a gagana.

Compared to that of an aldgoat, marid, or deathmouse, the milk of a steppe dzo is high in fat and flavor.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
This edible seaweed can be consumed raw, or dried into paper-like squares and wrapped around sticky rice.

A distant cousin of malm kelp, Ruby Tide kelp is harvested and dried in the sun to enhance flavor. Squares of the seaweed are cut and steeped in boiling water to create one of the savory broths used in Hingan cuisine.
A variety of algae found in the Ruby Sea, commonly harvested for its salt.

This infusion brewed from the powdered horn of a powerful beastkin is believed to improve crafting efficiency.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 15m

This infusion brewed from the powdered horn of a powerful beastkin is believed to improve crafting efficiency.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 15m

This infusion brewed from the powdered horn of a powerful beastkin is believed to improve crafting efficiency.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 15m

This sweet-smelling concoction enhances the rate at which your equipment gains spiritbond.

<UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 180m

column3: bottles of grade 1 reisui of strength
column5: When applied to items such as battle gear, this Far Eastern potation will, similarly to Eorzean dissolvents, dissolve away minute amounts of aether aspected to elements detrimental to strength, and by doing so, better attune the item and its wearer to the remaining beneficial elements.
