Ink fortified with koppranickel sand to improve aetherial conductivity.
Ink fortified with durium sand to improve aetherial conductivity.
Ink fortified with palladium sand to improve aetherial conductivity.
This alchemically formulated potation accelerates the growth of foliage.
This alchemically formulated potation accelerates the growth of foliage.
An adhesive substance created by grinding down the chitinous carapaces of beetles and mixing it with heated pine resin.
These pinkish crystals grow naturally on the shores of Loch Seld.
A sticky substance secreted by pine trees when their limbs are cut.
A translucent liquid extracted from persimmon wood by steeping it in hot water. Used in the tanning of raw animal hides.
A brownish variety of the mineral used by leatherworkers to tan animal hides. It is only found in the mountains of Eastern Aldenard.
This Far Eastern perennial has a biting aroma that even many Othardians find off-putting.
This annual is coveted by perfumers for its honey-sweet aroma.
Though recognized as a weed, this winter annual is edible and will oft be harvested in the late months for use in various Doman and Hingan dishes.
Though recognized as a weed, this winter annual is edible and will oft be harvested in the late months for use in various Doman and Hingan dishes.
Named for the protruding buds from which its bright-yellow flowers bloom, nipplewort is a common winter annual whose leaves are gathered for use in Othardian cuisine.
When steeped in boiling water, the leaves of this rare perennial change color, turning a bright bluish green.
An herb with an aroma so heavenly, it will cleanse both your soul and your palate of ill flavors (or so say merchants who would see you buy their stock).
An herb with an aroma so heavenly, the gods themselves must have blessed it (or so say merchants who would see you buy their stock).
The curved horn of a muud suud.
The twisted horn of a gazelle.
The massive ebon horn of a steppe dzo.
The powdery scales of a giant moth's wing.
A single adult bombfish can have as many as a thousand of these lightweight-yet-sturdy spines jutting from its body.
The thick chitinous head of a rhino beetle, complete with eyes, antennae, and mandibles.
Processed beech lumber.
Processed larch lumber.
Processed persimmon lumber.
Processed zelkova lumber.
Processed torreya lumber.
A rough-cut log of beech timber.
A rough-cut log of larch timber.
A rough-cut log of persimmon timber.
A rough-cut log of zelkova timber.
A rough-cut log of torreya timber.
This glossy red coating, made from the sap of the lacquer tree, is used to both color and preserve wooden crafts.
The thick branch of a beech tree.
The thick branch of a torreya tree.
A small nugget of impure koppranickel.
A small nugget of impure high steel.
An ingot of smelted koppranickel.
An ingot of smelted high steel.
A small nugget of impure durium.
An ingot of Doman iron, smelted using Far Eastern techniques.
An ingot of smelted durium.
An ingot of Doman steel, smelted using Far Eastern techniques.
A small nugget of impure palladium.
An ingot of smelted molybdenum.
An ingot of smelted palladium.
An ingot of smelted chromite.
Amber-colored sand consisting of tiny grains of koppranickel.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the metal koppranickel.
Jade-colored sand consisting of tiny grains of durium.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the metal Doman iron (also known as mochi iron for its resemblance to the Far Eastern rice cakes).
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the metal durium.
Metallic sand consisting of tiny grains of Doman iron.
Silver-colored sand consisting of tiny grains of palladium.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the metal molybdenum.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the metal palladium.
A decent-sized piece of rock containing the metal chromium.

Not to be outdone by their Near Eastern counterparts who perfected the aurum regis-hardening agent, Raziqcoat, several Far Eastern alchemists have joined together to create Domacoat─a substance capable of hardening palladium.
Not actually created from bones, this hot-burning fuel is the result of baking coal in an airless furnace at an extremely high temperature.
A yellow jewel.
A light-blue jewel.
A violet jewel.
A deep blue jewel.
Also known as “true jade,” this milky green stone is coveted by the Far Eastern elite.
A blood red jewel.
An uncut, unpolished stone containing what appears to be triphane.
An uncut, unpolished stone containing what appears to be kyanite.
An uncut, unpolished stone containing what appears to be star spinel.
An uncut, unpolished stone containing what appears to be azurite.
An uncut, unpolished stone containing what appears to be imperial jade.
An uncut, unpolished stone containing what appears to be rhodonite.
Several yalms of undyed, bright-red bloodhempen cloth wrapped around a short wooden distaff.
Coarse yarn spun from bloodhemp fiber.
A common grass found growing throughout Othard. From its stalks, bloodhempen yarn is created.
Several yalms of undyed ruby cotton cloth wrapped around a short wooden distaff.
Light yarn spun from ruby cotton.

The fibrous flower of a rare cotton plant that only grows <Emphasis>under</Emphasis> the Ruby Sea. As such, Eorzean scholars insist that the flora is in no way related to normal cotton, and is instead a unique variety of sea kelp.
Several yalms of undyed kudzu cloth wrapped around a short wooden distaff.
Thick, fibrous yarn spun from kudzu vines.

If allowed to grow unchecked, a single kudzu plant can cover an acre of forest in less than a single summer, blocking the sun from the plants it envelops. A large swath of the outer Black Shroud currently finds itself being slowly suffocated by the invasive weed.
Several yalms of undyed steppe serge wrapped around a short wooden distaff.
Soft, water-absorbent yarn spun from multiple varieties of hair sheared from beastkin of the Azim Steppe.
The regal mane of a halgai.
The long brown hair of a steppe manzasiri.
Though exhibiting a similar luster as normal silk, twinsilk is far more durable and resistant to discoloring.
A thin lustrous thread woven from countless silken strands pulled from a rare highland twincoon.
A massive cocoon spun by not one, but multiple highland erucas.

Cloth woven from the plant rhea. Due to the complexity of the spinning process, there are very few clothcrafters in the world who can produce this weave, making it extremely rare. Most known samples are in the possession of Far Eastern royalty.
A variety of ramie better suited to the climes of Far Eastern Othard.
Hempen cloth woven using age-old methods passed down for countless generations by Doman clothiers.
A large piece of cured gagana skin.
A large piece of cured gyuki hide.
A large piece of cured tiger skin.
A large piece of cured marid hide.
A large piece of cured gazelle hide.
A large piece of cured true griffin hide.
The rough skin of a majestic gagana.
The smooth hide of a devilish gyuki.
The striped skin of a ferocious tiger.
The thick hide of a mammoth marid.
The bristly hide of a steppe gazelle.
The downy hide of a true griffin.
Forbidden in many markets for the nefarious means with which it is extracted, this wax is cherished by leatherworkers for the luster it brings to tanned hides when applied.
Geological scholars claim that this sedimentary stone is actually comprised of the shells of thousands upon thousands of tiny sea creatures.
Unlike other sedimentary stone, slate has been compressed under the weight of mountains for so long that it is surprisingly hard, making it ideal for whetstones and grinding stones.
A whetstone carved from slate. Used for sharpening metal or stone blades.
A blackish mineral possibly containing trace amounts of the precious stone tourmaline.
A strange, pearlescent volcanic rock that expands tenfold upon heating in a kiln or forge.
A garnet-like mineral that, due to its extreme hardness, is used in grinding wheels.
A soft, clay-like soil believed to be formed of compacted yellow dust carried on the wind from faraway lands.
The elementally aspected remnants of aetherially reduced matter. This fine sand emits a weak glow indiscernible at gloaming.
The elementally aspected remnants of aetherially reduced matter. This fine sand emits a weak glow indiscernible at dawn.
The elementally aspected remnants of highly concentrated aetherially reduced mineral matter.
The elementally aspected remnants of highly concentrated aetherially reduced mineral matter.
The elementally aspected remnants of highly concentrated aetherially reduced mineral matter.

Though king of the five seas and beyond, scholars classify the liopleurodon with scalekin rather than wavekin.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 4 and higher.]
A freshwater fish named for its long, ribbon-like fins that it uses to both attract prey and distract predators.

This large carnivorous specimen is native to the southeastern reaches of the One River where the waters run slow and deep.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

The beauty of this small freshwater fish native to Yanxia is oft compared to the angels of ancient eastern scripture.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]
Like most saltwater eels, the blackfin snake eel of the Ruby Sea is a nocturnal hunter.
These tiny fish commonly found in the many shallow tributaries feeding into the upper One River rarely grow beyond a few ilms in length.
Despite their small size, sweatfish prefer the swift rapids of the One River's northern tributaries for the cover it provides them from predators.
By no means the most winsome of wavekin, the rock saltfish has adapted to survival in the saline waters of Loch Seld.
Near the bottom of the food chain, swift-swimming comet minnows serve as food for many of the larger fish that swim the waters of the Hathoeva and Velodyna Rivers.
This common variety of freshwater carp are found up and down the One River.
Named after the Hingan warriors whose grace and elegance in battle resemble the means by which this wavekin swims the turbid depths of the One River.
This bright-yellow fish is native to Gyr Abania and found in both the Hathoeva and Velodyna Rivers, sometimes as far west as East End.
A small, yet plump fish most commonly found in Hak Khaal, one of the One River's many narrow steppe tributaries.
The Yat goby is an eel-like bottom dweller named after the Azim Steppe tributary in which it is most commonly found.
Similar to a bass in appearance and flavor, the similarities end there, with this variety of meagre preferring the coastal waters of the Ruby Sea and the Glass Ocean to fresher rivers and lakes.
This distant relative to the carp can be found hunting the waters of the Hathoeva and Velodyna Rivers.
Some say this Ruby Sea shark earned its name from sailors long out of port who, upon seeing the shark's pale skin cresting above the waves, would reminisce of their favorite pleasure boat courtesan.
This queer horse-like wavekin swims upright, using two tiny fins near its head to slowly swim through the waters of extreme salinity it calls home.
This freshwater specimen of miniscule proportions can be found in almost any river and lake from central to eastern Othard.
Scholars are divided as to whether this wavekin native to the Ruby Sea and Glass Ocean is in fact a snake or an eel.

Groupers gather in swift currents of the Ruby Sea and the Rasen Kaikyo to feed on the abundant life drawn to the area.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
This violent scalekin has the jaws of a carpenter's vise. Many a careless fisher has lost a fingertip or three when navigating the snapper-rich waters of Loch Seld.
Remarkably similar in appearance to a shark, it is believed this salt lake fish periodically exposes its dorsal fin above the water's surface to frighten land predators such as bears.
Prehistoric drawings of this salt lake fish have been discovered on cave walls throughout Gyr Abania, suggesting that this particular species has endured at least six umbral eras.
The Abalathian bitterling's ivory white skin easily distinguishes it from its silver cousins also found in the freshwater rivers and lakes of Gyr Abania.
One of only a few fresh water sharks discovered in Eorzea, the steelshark can primarily be found in the rivers and lakes of Gyr Abania.
Though a cousin to the Hak bitterling, the waters of Tao Khaal have taken the Tao bitterling on a slightly different evolutionary path.
This large goby uses its natural black and brown mottling to conceal itself in the sandy bed of the Slow Wash.
Called “akame” or “red eye” in the Far East for the unique color of this freshwater fish's optical organs.
This freshwater fish is known to change the color of its skin come spawning season.

This saltwater fish has a distinct crimson coloring that makes it popular amongst aquarium owners.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]
A delicious, fatty freshwater fish native to the Velodyna and Hathoeva Rivers.
A unique variety of freshwater charr found only in the waters near Heather Falls.

A plump freshwater wavekin with pearlescent scales and a name that sounds better than the fish tastes.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

The pale yellow glow emitted by this freshwater fish is believed to be caused by unbalanced levels of aspected aether in the wavekin's humours.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

The pale blue glow emitted by this freshwater fish is believed to be caused by unbalanced levels of aspected aether in the wavekin's humours.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

Similar to the sea horse, the hanatatsu swims “standing,” though instead of resembling a beast of burden, this saltwater fish has taken on the appearance of a sprig of coral.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
A wildly misnamed freshwater crab with a highly durable carapace.
This succulent pink-fleshed fish commonly found in the Hathoeva and Velodyna Rivers will oft command a high price in local markets.
This freshwater crustacean is widely found in lakes and marshes across the Three Great Continents.
This feisty freshwater fish is found throughout the Black Shroud.
This freshwater betta is native to the lakes and marshes of eastern Gyr Abania.
This massive whiskered wavekin can be found lurking in the calm, turbid lakes and marshes of eastern Gyr Abania.
Though only ever seen by fishers who spend more time telling tales in taverns than actually fishing, the pagan pirarucu can supposedly be found in the highland lakes and swamps of eastern Gyr Abania.
A freshwater fish commonly found in the lakes and marshes dotting the eastern end of Abalathia's Spine.

The Far Eastern gilfish was first introduced to Eorzea by Othardian merchants hoping their platinum sheen would make them attractive to wealthy nobles. Now the freshwater fish can be found in rivers and lakes across the realm.
A hardy amphibian found in the relatively warm-watered lakes of eastern Abalathia's Spine. The plump legs make for a fine meal.
A rare type of luminescent moss found in the lightless depths of Far Eastern lakes, as well as in caves. Slight currents cause the moss to form into a ball as it grows.
This particular variety of loach can be found in the lakes, rivers, and swamps of northern Gyr Abania.
A succulent freshwater crab remarkably found only in the Peaks lake of Grymm.
A succulent freshwater shrimp remarkably found only in the Peaks lake of Enid.
The pristine white shell of this freshwater crustacean makes it nigh invisible when the wavekin is hiding amongst rocks or sand of a similar hue.
A lifetime of swimming against strong, yet slow river currents have left this freshwater fish bereft of most fatty flesh.
An amphibian commonly found living in the myriad lakes and swamps of Gyr Abania.
A freshwater fish native to the wetlands of Gyr Abania.
Possessed of the unique ability to survive for extended periods out of water, the meditator will periodically “bathe” on the banks of the rivers and lakes in which it resides.
A freshwater fish so enormous, even the legends sung of the elusive wavekin do not do it justice.
This distant cousin to the Coerthan bonytongue can be found dwelling in the freshwater lakes and rivers of Gyr Abania.
A small carnivorous fish found solely in the isolated Gyr Abanian pond known as the Bull's Bath.
This freshwater fish is possessed of an eye on both the top and bottom of its head, allowing it to simultaneously spy threats above and below the water, should the need arise.
Not a swordfish, but a sword-like fish found in the rivers of Gyr Abania.
An aptly named freshwater fish native to the rivers of Gyr Abania.
One of the rare fish found in the Nhaama Desert's even rarer freshwater oases.
These small fries found primarily in the caves of Gyr Abania rarely grow to more than one or two ilms.
This lake snail feeds by attaching itself to the bones of drowned animals.
The still waters of Dimwold are teeming with these fish who, to the untrained eye, appear naught more than fallen leaves.
This glowing orb is actually a colony of rare luminescent algae found in the caves of eastern Gyr Abania.
This odd whiskered fish is found only in the sheltered waters of the Comet's Tail.
The backs of these freshwater crabs are adorned with colorful colonies of water-resistant fungus.
This variety of grass carp is most often found in the northeastern Eorzean river from which it earns its name.
One of several varieties of carp found in the Velodyna River, this particular species is immediately recognizable from its pitch-black skin.
This eel-like freshwater fish has been blessed with the capacity to emit an electric charge that can prove deadly to smaller wavekin.

Once common throughout the Gyr Abanian highlands, overfishing has relegated the remainder of the species to Mirage Creek.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
This freshwater fish will bury itself deep in the gravel-littered beds of rivers, making it a difficult catch.
These small saltwater fish swim in massive schools, using their sheer numbers to ensure that even if a few stragglers are swallowed, the species will endure.
This common silver fish will travel back and forth between the Ruby Sea and the Glass Ocean searching for food.
The abundance of these translucent amorphs to the volcanic island of Hells' Lid was an invitation to a ill-conceived moniker, most likely given by a rum-soaked pirate.
A piece of sharp crimson coral, widely found throughout the Ruby Sea.
A piece of sharp azure coral, widely found throughout the Ruby Sea.
A piece of sharp milky white coral, widely found throughout the Ruby Sea.
One of few brightly colored fish native to the Ruby Tide.
Its sheer dominance over other life in the Ruby Sea has earned this sizable wavekin the title “dafu,” or literally, the top dog...er, fish.

Fishers seeking to land ocean-dwelling swordfish must take care not to accidentally impale themselves on the wavekin's serrated blade-like maw.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
At a glance, one might mistake this queerly shaped denizen of the Ruby Sea for an errant piece of seaweed.
This flat bottom dweller spends most of its life skittering about the floors of the Glass Ocean, but can also be found in the Ruby Sea.
This giant shark regularly hunts the waters of the coast of the Isle of Zekki, and has been known to attack the pirates and fishers who frequent its strands.
A rarely seen giant squid, thought to be the inspiration for 35% of all pirate chanties sung on the Ruby Sea.
A highly elusive giant octopus, so rarely seen that not a single pirate chanty sung on the Red Sea mentions the poor cephalopod.
A unique saltwater fish that will jump from the water to evade predators, using its pectoral fins to glide across the ocean surface.
A saltwater fish that will puff its spike-laden body to bursting to protect itself when provoked.
The shell of this bivalve mollusk is ribbed like the “uchiwa” hand fans used by Hingan festival-goers in summer.
A saltwater fish as stubborn as its name suggests. It is pure coincidence that it also has a hard bony plate protecting its tiny brain.
One of the most popular ingredients in Hingan sushi, the giant Glass tuna are thought to follow the strong ocean currents for thousands of malms in their lifetime.
These tiny freshwater crustaceans can be found in relative abundance in the flooded rice paddies of Yanxia.
One of the most common shrimp found in the Ruby Sea.

Similar to the globefish, the fugu will puff up its body to frighten away potential predators. Those who do not heed the wavekin's warning and devour it anyway will most certainly succumb to the lethal poison found in the fugu's flesh.
A large freshwater fish named for the levin-manipulating technique mastered by the ninja of Doma.
The body of this rare freshwater fish is entirely void of pigment.
Despite the insistence of Yanxian villagers, the freshwater dragonfish is ten parts fish, zero parts dragon.
Just as do the salmon of Eorzea, the steely blue salmon of the Far East spend their lives in the sea before returning to the freshwater rivers where they were born to spawn and die.
A mottled freshwater carp of middling size native to the southern reaches of the One River.
A large, slow-swimming freshwater fish found primarily in Yanxia's Plum Spring.
Though named for its lengthy whiskers, this catfish's most ready feature is not its moustache, but the wavy scale-like patterns on its back.
Those seeking to land a plum gazer must travel to the secluded Plum Spring, hidden deep in Yanxia's Gensui Chain.
This regal freshwater fish has a distinct white and black mottling which, while giving the wavekin an air of majesty, also makes it easy to spot by predators.
An extremely common fish found throughout Yanxia, and a popular dish amongst the realm's residents.
A thin freshwater eel that can be found living amongst the reeds growing in the Valley of the Fallen Rainbow.
This brightly colored freshwater fish of Far Eastern origin is a favorite amongst aquarium owners.
A freshwater fish found in rivers across the entire Othardian continent.
A freshwater fish extremely common to many of the One River's northern tributaries. Its name literally translates to “river fish.”
A swift freshwater fish that, when swimming near the surface of the One River tributaries in which it is commonly found, appears to skip through the rivers' reeds.
A small freshwater fish found in the arid southern grasslands bordering the Nhaama Desert.
This violent fish native to the Azim Steppe prefers the calm waters of a lake or wetland to the swift moving currents of a river.
The skytear can be found in the quick-flowing shallow rapids near a river's source rather than in the deeper, slow-moving waters downstream.
A red-shelled freshwater crustacean found in abundance in the lakes and rivers of the Azim Steppe.
A white-shelled freshwater crustacean found in abundance in the lakes and rivers of the Azim Steppe.
This swift-moving freshwater fish can be found up and down the One River.
Highly developed scales and spines set this sculpin apart from its western counterparts.
A horn-shaped fish native to the dark bogs of Dimwold.
A common variety of koi found in almost every region on Othard.
This freshwater fish has a billowy, curtain-like dorsal fin that it uses to confuse predators.
A freshwater cousin of the lightscale with scales as hard as its name suggests.
The massive eastern pike is technically classified as a freshwater fish. The breed, however, can survive the brackish waters of the Hathoeva and Velodyna River deltas.
This freshwater fish native to the bogs of Dimwold will oft conceal itself beneath the planks of the Wraithwalk for protection.

As is the case with the little Thalaos, the little Perykos is anything but small. Though normally only found in the Indigo Deep, this lord of the North Isle of Endless Summer can sometimes be found swimming in the five seas and beyond...yet for what reason, no one knows.
A tiny Ruby Sea mollusk with a beautiful spiral shell that is sought by jewelry makers across the Far East.

This saltwater cousin to the puffers changes color several times during its development, and it is only in the final years of adulthood that it bears the hue from which it earns its moniker.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
This denizen of the Glass Ocean is one of the largest fish of its type ever recorded.

According to Hingan fishers, it was not until the past twenty summers that the regal silverside began appearing in their nets. It is popular opinion that the fish may have been introduced via bilge water dumped by foreign trade bulks.
A saltwater fish that exhibits a peculiar symbiotic relationship with spiny lobsters.
While “hopping” out of the water will aid this saltwater species in escaping larger fish, the action attracts flocks of hungry seagulls that will harry the schools for entire turns of the sun.
A freshwater cousin of the hardscale with scales as light as its name suggests.
This highly poisonous saltwater fish can survive for long periods of time in freshwater rivers, and can, on occasion, be found as far as ten malms upstream.
An eel's size is proportional to the amount it eats. The giant freshwater eels of the One River eat...a lot.
While abundant in the sea, hermit crabs are quite rare in fresh water, possibly due to the lack of available homes. The kamina crab is one example.
The spider crab's spindly legs carry the deep-sea crustacean hundreds of malms across their migratory routes.
The elongated forehead of this saltwater species is compared to the nose of a tengu─a legendary dog-like creature of Far Eastern legend.
This saltwater wavekin uses both the size and color of its fins to its advantage, allowing it to, for all intents and purposes, disappear in the darker depths of the sea.

Unlike those of the mystical zebra, the pronounced “stripes” upon this wavekin's back are more accurately compared to a tiger's spots.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
The sharp, bone-like protrusions on this carnivorous mollusk's massive shell give it the comb-like appearance from which it earns its name.
This sluggardly wartfish native to the One River somehow has more warts than a common wartfish, if that can be believed.
It would not be called a common whelk if this whelk was not found as abundantly as it is across the whole of Othard.
This impossibly monstrous freshwater fish grew impossibly monstrous despite a diet of mostly river grasses.

The Ruby Sea hatchetfish earns its name from its overgrown head which, if you squint hard enough, might appear similar to the head of a timberlord's hatchet.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]
This spindly saltwater fish spurns the colder currents of the north in favor of the warm waters along Othard and Ilsabard's southern coasts.
Garden eels spend most of their lives buried in sandy sea bottoms, emerging only to hunt and to mate.
Named for its shape and not its flavor, this repugnant slug-like mass is found throughout the Glass Ocean and Ruby Sea.
This enormous saltwater bass can be highly territorial, devouring anything and everything that passes through its chosen demesne.
A saltwater wavekin commonly avoided by fishers due to the extreme amount of toxins found in its flesh.
A deep-red relative of the Doman crayfish.
A dark-scaled carp found in the One River, easily identified by its queer downward-pointing eyes.
Named after an ancient Far Eastern currency, this bivalve mollusk is most commonly found in the lakes and rivers of Yanxia.

A large carnivorous wavekin that dwells in the warm currents of the southern seas.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
This large variety of trevally is given the name ronin for its tendency to journey the warm southern seas in solitude.
The most delicious of saltwater groupers...if the merchants selling it for thrice the price of a regular grouper are to be believed.
The shell of this warm-water sea mollusk is twisted like the turbans worn by the dhalmel drivers of Thavnair.
These spiny five-limbed invertebrates survive by feeding on the flesh of dead fish fallen to the sea floor.
These giant crabs hide themselves amongst the plants that grow on a river's bed, the moss growing on their claws used as camouflage.
A decent-sized fish found in the One River.
An ancient breed of freshwater fish found with little frequency in the One River.
One of the most widespread squid species on Hydaelyn.

A common saltwater fish doing its best scad impression.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
Snow crabs live in deep waters, scurrying hither and thither across the ocean floor in search of carrion.
A saltwater fish found in both the Glass Ocean and the Ruby Sea.

This freshwater fish is found on both the Othardian east coast and in Shishu─the Hingan island upon which sits Kugane.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

This long-living freshwater cod is commonly found in the One River.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]

A thin, eel-like fish native to Nagxia, but found throughout the One River.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

A large, reddish-orange fish with distinctively enormous eyes to help it see in the murky depths of the Ruby Sea.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
This Far Eastern crustacean has not only the stripes, but also the ferocity of a Yanxian tiger.
The tengu fan, named for its round, flat shape, will emit electric shocks from its body when threatened. Though the shocks cannot kill, they do stun, affording the fish ample opportunity to flee.
When viewed from the side, this sea mollusk's shell looks like a turban; however, when viewed from above, its radiating spines give it the appearance of a twinkling star.
A delicious freshwater fish with the most jejune moniker of all the One River's aquatic denizens.
Steppe bullfrogs can be found across both Yanxia and Nagxia and are easily identifiable by their deep, bellowing mating croaks.

This large, aggressive freshwater fish will “charge” most anything moving, regardless of its size.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]

Second only to the blue-fish in mediocrity of monikers, the freshwater redfin of the One River─unsurprisingly─has bright-red fins.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
A cousin of the sundisc, the moondisc also features celestial patterns upon its body, though its are decidedly brighter to serve as camouflage in the white-bedded waters of Loch Seld.
Similar to most wavekin that have taken up residence in Loch Seld, the bleached bonytongue is almost entirely white.
The salt shark has an elongated body that it can bend like an eel, allowing it to navigate Loch Seld's obstacle-strewn lakebed in search for prey.
Very few species of octopus have been discovered in Loch Seld, but those that have─such as the king's mantle─are magnificently monstrous.
This variety of sea anemone emits a soft green glow when its tentacles are disturbed.
This large saltwater predator can be found in the waters off both the eastern and western coasts of Hingashi.
Though dubbed a salmon, this particular variety does not journey downstream to the sea, spending its entire life in the river where it was born.
Hingan folklore has that all hot springs were once dug from the ground by these hardy crustaceans.

This freshwater fish commonly found in the upper One River is also known as the Mol gudgeon, the Kahkoli gudgeon, the Dataqi gudgeon, the Horo gudgeon, and after whichever other Xaela tribe that insists their ancestors first caught the species.
A small bivalve mollusk found living in the sands of the One River.

Grass sharks are massive, their size rivaling that of even the Glass Ocean's greatest predators─an amazing feat considering grass sharks live their entire lives in the confines of the One River.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
The typhoon shrimp is one of only a few shrimp species that can survive the toxically salty waters of Loch Seld.
This bivalve mollusk grows in abundance on boulders and statues submerged in Loch Seld.

The white coloring of the salt urchin's spines make them difficult to see on Loch Seld's colorless lakebed. Those who choose to wade through the shallows should always take care to protect their feet.
A carpenter crab's claws are powerful enough to cut through solid wood. Whether or not a carpenter crab has ever constructed something from that wood remains unconfirmed.
This massive crustacean found in both the Ruby Sea and the Glass Ocean is considered a delicacy in the Far East, and is a luxury oft too extravagant for any but the richest of nobles to partake in.
There is no doubt that the mitsukuri shark's most defining feature is its katana-like mouth and the tales it has spawned of poor fishers being impaled.

A variety of bubble eye goldfish selectively bred by Doman royalty for innumerable generations.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 1 and higher.]

There are many theories as to why this remarkable breed of One River squeaker swims tail first, yet most have been dismissed as feeble attempts to explain what simply cannot be explained, such as why the sky is blue or why tides come in and the tides go out.
Though smaller than the dusk herald, the dawn herald is as commonly found in the waters of the One River as its close cousin.
An ashen-shelled snail found throughout Loch Seld. Cooking the gastropods in their shells with garlic and herbs is the preferred method of consumption.

The white sturgeon is believed by some scholars to simply be normal sturgeons exhibiting albinism─a rare trait that became common once all the darker sturgeons were poached from Loch Seld on account of them being easy to see.
One of Loch Seld's largest native species.
The unique shape and coloration of the batfish makes this denizen of the Ruby Sea a highly sought-after specimen amongst collectors.
Unlike sea breams, this quirky cousin will travel back and forth 'twixt the brackish waters of a river's delta and the fresher waters upstream.
The snipe eels of the One River will never grow plumper than an ilm or two in diameter, but can stretch to several yalms in length.

A rare freshwater fish native to Yanxia and the Azim Steppe.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]

The dusk herald is a fair-sized fish commonly found in the One River.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
This freshwater perch is found up and down the One River.
While given the modifier Abalathian, this particular pipira will not be found in the Spine's western or even central regions, preferring the biting salty waters of the Lochs.
The steel loach's scintillant silver body reflects sunlight in a manner that makes the fish difficult to spot in its native Loch Seld.
The whitish grey skin of this large flatfish allows it to hide itself on the bottom of Loch Seld with such efficiency that for years Ala Mhigans thought the species extinct.

A striped carnivore that hunts the Ruby Sea.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]
A rare, sea-dwelling scalekin infamous for its gaping maw lined with multiple rows of blade-like teeth, though official observations by scholars put the fang count at no more than a few score.

Let not its dolphin-like appearance fool you. The ichthyosaur is a ravenous scalekin that feeds on squid, fish, and the occasional man overboard.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 3 and higher.]

A unique saltwater fish featuring astonishingly overgrown dorsal and anal fins.

[Suitable for display in aquariums tier 2 and higher.]
An extremely rare freshwater fish whose face is covered in countless whisker-like protrusions.
This large freshwater fish's skin features brilliant streaks of fiery yellow and orange.
Special glands within the fickle krait's body create a deadly poison feared by fishers and coveted by assassins.
This tiny species' skin exhibits a violet hue rarely seen in freshwater fish.
A rare white freshwater fish believed to harbor the soul of a once-proud steppe stallion.
The descendants of sea tuna believed by scholars to have arrived in Loch Seld during the great flood that ended the Fifth Astral Era.
This heavily armored crab is one of few species adapted to the hypersalinated waters of Loch Seld.
A pigmentless fish found solely in Loch Seld.
A rare breed of sunfish that can survive only in waters exhibiting extreme salinity.
An aggressive scalekin native to the saline waters of Loch Seld.
A common (★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
An uncommon (★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
An uncommon (★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
An uncommon (★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
An uncommon (★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.

A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.

A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
An epic (★★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
An epic (★★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
An epic (★★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
An epic (★★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A legendary (★★★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A legendary (★★★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A note of promise received from Rowena for the delivery of tomes of regional folklore.
A light, billowy silk woven using traditional methods of the Nagxian people.
Leaves of a low-growing shrub native to the plains of Nagxia. The leaves contain high concentrations of tannin, an ingredient necessary in tanning leather.
Despite supposedly being woven countless generations past, this cloth appears as it was crafted yesterday.
A beastkin hide tanned using traditional Nagxian methods.

A banded chest containing a complete set of chivalrous armor, an antiquated Galatyn, and an antiquated Evalach.

Cannot be opened in instanced areas such as dungeons, PvP areas, or raids.

A banded chest containing a complete set of pacifist's attire and a pair of antiquated Sudarshana Chakra.

Cannot be opened in instanced areas such as dungeons, PvP areas, or raids.

A banded chest containing a complete set of brutal armor and an antiquated Farsha.

Cannot be opened in instanced areas such as dungeons, PvP areas, or raids.

A banded chest containing a complete set of storyteller's attire and an antiquated Failnaught.

Cannot be opened in instanced areas such as dungeons, PvP areas, or raids.

A banded chest containing a complete set of seventh heaven attire and an antiquated Aymur.

Cannot be opened in instanced areas such as dungeons, PvP areas, or raids.

A banded chest containing a complete set of seventh hell attire and an antiquated Vanargand.

A banded chest containing a complete set of kage-kakushi garb and a pair of antiquated Nagi.

A banded chest containing a complete set of constellation attire and an antiquated Pleiades.

Cannot be opened in instanced areas such as dungeons, PvP areas, or raids.

A banded chest containing a complete set of myochin armor and an antiquated Kiku-ichimonji.

Cannot be opened in instanced areas such as dungeons, PvP areas, or raids.

A banded chest containing a complete set of duelist's attire and an antiquated Murgleis.

A detailed record of recent Eorzean history─so detailed, in fact, that all who read it come to swear they experienced the events firsthand.

Use to instantly complete all main scenario quests up through “The Far Edge of Fate.” Cannot be used outside large settlements. Automatic logout will commence upon usage.

A freshwater fish easily recognizable for its vivid black and white stripes.

Despite the insistence of fishers raised on colorful local folklore, the massive knob atop this freshwater fish's head does not contain hidden treasure.

Its Hingan name roughly translating to “floating tree,” this variety of Eastern sunfish neither floats nor is a tree.

A slightly corrosive paste concocted by Doman goldsmiths that, when applied to certain accessories, heightens their attributes by restoring their luster.
A note of promise received from Rowena for the delivery of Allagan tomestones of mendacity or poetics.

Garlond Ironworks engineers believe this device to be an attempt by Allagan scientists to increase tomestone capacity, while keeping overall size relatively small. This may have become the next standard in tomestone data storage...had not their civilization been inconveniently wiped from the realm.

A heavy chest containing a diamond weapon.

Weapon type determined by current job or class at time of opening. Cannot be opened in instanced areas such as dungeons, PvP areas, or raids.
Comprising the front end of a shark-class submersible, this bow has been reinforced to double as a battering ram for subduing unruly sea creatures.
Comprising the top of a shark-class submersible, the bridge houses all of the equipment necessary for the vessel's crew to navigate the unplumbed depths of the Ruby Sea and beyond.

Comprising the center of a shark-class submersible, this ovoid hull is multi-walled to stabilize and maintain pressure within so that the vessel's crew does not succumb to the crushing weight of the waters it navigates. Several sturdy rudder fins serve to increase maneuverability.
Comprising the rear end of a shark-class submersible, this stern contains the unique independent engine which propels the craft.
Unlike the bows of most submersibles, the unkiu-class model is outfitted with rudder fins usually relegated to the stern.
Designed by the Onishishu─a collective of skilled Far Eastern craftsmen─this submersible bridge differs dramatically in build from those built in the West.

Comprising the center of an unkiu-class submersible, this ovoid hull is multi-walled to stabilize and maintain pressure within so that the vessel's crew does not succumb to the crushing weight of the waters it navigates. Supplemental propulsion engines have been affixed to the sides to increase underwater speed.
Comprising the rear end of an unkiu-class submersible, this stern contains a double propeller engine.

This crystalline prism captures the likeness of a piece of equipment and projects it onto another object of comparable form and function.

[Necessary to project glamours.]
The elemental energies of this unstable crystal are in a perpetual state of flux.
A foul feather plucked from the Eurekan nightmare, Pazuzu.
A crystal discovered in Eureka Anemos─a region where the elemental aspect leans heavily to wind.

column5: Common in the Far East, futons are thin down-filled mattresses laid directly on the floor instead of upon a frame. After use, they are generally rolled up and stored in a closet until needed again.
An expertly woven tapestry displayed during Hatching-tide festivities.
An indoor lantern designed to resemble the oddest of otters.
A Heavensturn decoration displayed at homes and places of business. The spinning umbrella is thought to bring fortune as long as an object remains atop.

When faced with the dilemma of adorning his wall with a normal chronometer or a chronometer carved in the adorable likeness of a moogle, it is said the dread (though most likely nonexistent) pirate Mustbeard replied with a hearty “arrr” and found room for both.

A round desk carved to resemble Byakko, one of the mystic Four Lords of the Far East.

※One per estate only.

A regal throne, fit for a king...or emperor that also happens to be a giant white tiger.

※One per estate only.
So realistic is this stuffed spriggan that many a mage has lost face after sending one up in a gout of sorcerous flame.
A trophy awarded to those who “left their mark” in Season Six of the Feast.
Without proper advertisement, some may mistake Valentione's Day for any other day, albeit one with far more pink balloons.

To create these festive balloons, the bladders of various flying fish caught in the Sea of Clouds were dried, colored, then stamped with the House Valentione coat of arms before being filled with heated air to keep them afloat.

Aromatic loaves of freshly baked bread fill this wicker basket to the brim.

※Cannot be retrieved once used.
※Can be used up to 10 times.

A charming recreation of the chocobo Alpha, filled with the feathers of a fowl less fortunate.

A faithful replication of the selfsame set used every morning by Aymeric de Borel himself.

An interior wall built with genuine kiln-fired bricks.
A space-saving cupboard that can be mounted anywhere there is a wall.
The vegetables contained within this basket have not been approved for consumption. Dine at your own risk.
A low partition cut with a hole to provide estates with the illusion of more space than actually exists.
An island for kitchens designed to resemble those carts used by hawkers in city markets.
A decorative cabinet designed in the Old World Sharlayan style.
A decorative wardrobe designed in the Old World Sharlayan style.
A small tub crafted to resemble a summoner's best friend. Just large enough for two.
From scalpels to saws, panaceas to placebos, this basic set of medical devices has everything the unlicensed surgeon needs.
Save space in your cupboards for liquor and fruitcake by hanging all your kitchen appliances from hooks.
A frightening mask of Far Eastern design. Perfect for children's bedrooms and nurseries.
A set of Hingan bottles and cups perfect for taking one's evening refreshment with guests─though using it to take one's afternoon refreshment alone is not unheard of.
A large white panel used by acting troupes as a simple backdrop for plays.
Those without a deathly fear of snakes claim this plush doll to be one of the most beautiful ever crafted. Most ophidiophobes, however, would beg to differ.

A small, reinforced glass tank that, when filled with water, can serve as a home for select wavekin caught in the wild. The higher an aquarium's tier, the larger the specimens that can be kept within.
※Private chambers (apartments), cottages, houses, and mansions can host 4, 6, 8, and 10 aquariums, respectively.

A reinforced glass tank that, when filled with water, can serve as a home for select wavekin caught in the wild. The higher an aquarium's tier, the larger the specimens that can be kept within.
※Private chambers (apartments), cottages, houses, and mansions can host 4, 6, 8, and 10 aquariums, respectively.
Not one to be humbled by craftsmen of the East, a prominent Eorzean lamp maker conceived this fixture he hopes will become the new standard in home and garden lighting.
A cast-iron wood stove designed after a fateful encounter with a voidsent bomb.
A decorative pillar designed in the Hingan fashion.
What better way to tell unwanted visitors, “can't you see I'm busy?” than by strewing stacks of important-looking documents all about your humble abode?
Countless varieties of rouges, putties, and talcums commonly used by mummers to prepare themselves for their acts.
Because one wouldn't dare hang a dress on a coat hanger.
An oversized locker used by mummers to house not only their costumes, but their various tools of the trade.
A tiered dais used in the Far East to display dolls. Adapted in Eorzea for use on Little Ladies' Day.
Because one wouldn't dare hang a coat on a dress hanger.
Make profane offerings from the comfort of your home with this sinister altar to the high voidsent Pazuzu.

This permit allows the hiring of Hingan servants known as “hokonin” on the estate.

※Private chambers (apartments), cottages, houses, and mansions can host 4, 6, 8, and 10 vendors, respectively.

A pushcart filled with thousands upon thousands of fragrant roses (give or take a few thousand).
A low-growing hedge, expertly pruned and trimmed into the shape of an L.
A controlled cluster of bamboo cut from a Yanxian forest for display in private gardens.
Scalding water tapped from the very bowels of the land, and collected in a quaint rock pool certain to draw the envy of neighbors.
A wall that matches the design of those used in Aymeric de Borel's very manor.
Smooth, elegant floor tiling made of polished marble.
A lavish light fixture that hearkens to days long past.

A fully functional moogle-themed orchestrion for the moogle-lover who has everything...but a fully functional moogle-themed orchestrion.

※One orchestrion of any type per estate only.

An authentic reproduction of the perfect way to say “I love you” without having your hands torn to shreds by thousands of prickly rose thorns.

Select flowers can be displayed within.
An authentic reproduction of one of hundreds of hand-drawn images posted about Ul'dah in preparation for Little Ladies' Day.

There is nothing quite as ephemeral as a single pink cherry petal dancing in the wind as it makes its long descent from tree to earth, just as there is nothing quite as exhilarating as jumping in an authentic reproduction of a drift of tens of thousands of said petals.
An authentic reproduction of an interior wall designed to complement private Hatching–tide celebrations.

Several hard, brown bulbs the size of a gigantoad's eye.

※For use in planters.

This horn of bone emits a plangent tone that summons the Red Hare, warsteed of the great Ganen himself.
The prophetic song of this stout flute is said to summon a kamuy blessed by Lord Byakko himself.
A horn of ivory used to summon a towering marid.
A thin rectangular piece of what appears to be cermet. Placing it near your Air Force mobile assault unit will magically bring the machine to life.
A thin rectangular piece of what appears to be cermet. Placing it near your magitek death claw will magically bring the machine to life.
A rough-hewn horn of petrified bone that, when blown, emits a somber tone that summons a supposedly tamed tyrannosaur.
When held aloft, this pendant magically summons half of a flying heart. The right half.
When held aloft, this pendant magically summons half of a flying heart. The left half.
The sneeze-like blare of this horn summons Typhon, for reasons that no one knows and everyone refuses to find out.

Cute and cudgely.

Got to be the fuzziest.

Lighter than air─er...water.

Use item to acquire the aurelia polyp minion.

Beckons you to enter his barrel of sin, but don't go in.

Use item to acquire the Gold Whisker minion.

Part lion, part dog, all lion-dog.

column5:
Once the nightmare of shopkeeps alone, highly detailed models such as this one have gained popularity amongst adventurers as means of selling unneeded accoutrements, displaying hard-won ensembles, and unnerving unsuspecting visitors.

※Private chambers (apartments), cottages, houses, and mansions can hold 4, 6, 8, and 10 facilities, respectively.
This peculiar contraption creates illusions by weaving together myriad shades of light. Produces a shower of translucent hearts.
This peculiar contraption creates illusions by weaving together myriad shades of light. Produces a pair of ethereal wings reminiscent of cathedral glass.
A round table for all the chocobo- and food-lovers out there.
A chair for all of (well, one of) the chocobo-lovers out there.
A tall indoor lamp with an odder otter motif.
A large dining table for all the chocobo-, food-, and chocobo-as-food-lovers out there.
A trophy awarded to those who “left their mark” in Season Nine of the Feast.
A trophy awarded to those who “left their mark” in Season Ten of the Feast.

A warming dish of familiar vegetables simmered for bells in a rich sauce of thickened milk.

※Cannot be retrieved once used.
※Can be used up to 10 times.

Meal benefits when used:
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Spell Speed Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +4% (Max 10)
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>VIT Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +4% (Max 12)
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Gear Durability Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +2
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m
  (Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
An elegant relief depicting one of the Four Lords, alive with dancing flame.
A sizable potted tree, perpetually in bloom with redolent magenta flowers.
An artistic ink rendering of the spectacularly reconstructed Doman Enclave.

A festive wall decoration dominated by All Saints' Wake motifs. If one did not know better than to suspect the troupe of trickery, one might think this “reward” merely a hastily assembled hodgepodge of spare party decorations.

In the spirit of All Saints' Wake, each of these pastries is pumpkin-flavored...except for the pumpkin-shaped one, which was deemed thematically sufficient regardless. Also in the spirit of All Saints' Wake, there are more of them than is advisable to consume in one sitting.

Meal benefits when used:
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Critical Hit Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +4% (Max 10)
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>VIT Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +4% (Max 12)
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Gear Durability Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m
  (Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
An adhesive wall decoration to make any witches in your company this All Saints' Wake feel at home.

A potted conifer displayed in homes during the Starlight Celebration. Its snowy color will make your decor sumptuous─and your gatherings lively as you argue with friends and neighbors over whether it is superior to the more traditional green.
Festive treats for those who prefer to express their Starlight spirit through eating until they lose consciousness.
This indoor frosty snowman will never melt away. He'll be there forever. Watching. Waiting.
The detritus of many happy Starlight Celebration surprises.

A flaky-crusted tart with a slight acidity that complements its pleasant sweetness, so enormous that it should only be served at parties. Of course, sometimes a party can be just one hungry homeowner and a clean fork. Or a dirty one. It doesn't really matter.

※Cannot be retrieved once used.
※Can be used up to 10 times.

Meal benefits when used:
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Tenacity Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +4% (Max 10)
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>VIT Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +4% (Max 12)
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Gear Durability Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +2
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>EXP Bonus:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> +3%
  <UIForeground>F201F8</UIForeground><UIGlow>F201F9</UIGlow>Duration:<UIGlow>01</UIGlow><UIForeground>01</UIForeground> 30m
  (Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
A mounted sample of the luminous euhedral crystals that grow uninhibited on the sea floor.
An elegant bouquet for romantic occasions, each bloom painstakingly selected by the florist Tanie.
Unlike those attached to non-imitation windows, these louvered shutters will ever remain pristine as they add a touch of the rustic to your interior decor.
This set for aspiring culinary artists includes soft, child-safe replicas of everything one might need in the kitchen, including a helpful Miqo'te poissonnier.
Spare a thought for the poor carpenter who toiled to make this furnishing both simple and elegant as you inevitably pile as many objects as physically possible atop its shelves.
A knitter's work is never done. In this case, literally.
An adventurer never leaves home without his compass! And his waterskin. And his lantern. And his potions. And his telescope. And his books. Really, an adventurer needs to learn to pack a bit lighter.
This storage unit is packed with enough spices, herbs, oils, and other ingredients to satisfy even the most dedicated culinarian.
One could raise an entire army of ducks with this much bread. Hypothetically.
For weary adults who have spent overmuch on alligator pears and cannot afford to live alone.
A large and lovely woven vessel. Be advised that if a Lalafell fits in it, she will sits in it.
Home is where the heap of unfolded undergarments is.
There's no better way to vaunt your wealth than buying three nearly identical pairs of trousers and refusing to wear any of them.
Opaque vessels of assorted size, perhaps containing flour and sugar. Or cookies. Or bugs.
Dishes for those with simple tastes and many friends.
A half-dozen goblets for fancy parties. Cupbearer not included.
A sturdy wooden display. For the <Emphasis>good</Emphasis> plates, not the <Emphasis>food</Emphasis> plates.
A lush partition covered floor-to-ceiling in ivy and assorted ferns.
A large square of cerulean tiling with a built-in drain.
A square of tiling used to prevent walls from becoming so waterlogged that the house slowly but surely collapses in on itself.
Such neatly folded and extraordinarily fluffy towels can only have been purloined from an expensive inn.
Does one truly require a sofa if he has this many pillows?
An elegant two-tiered water feature. Perhaps doubting that potential purchasers would be patient enough to wait for real ones to appear, the sculptor helpfully attached model birds as well.
Myriad tiny rocks that await your landscaping pleasure.
All these squares make a circle.
Durable yet fuzzy loop carpet with a checkerboard pattern.
A contemporary light fixture designed with the Twelve as its primary theme.
An interior wall of pale unvarnished wood.
Comprising the front end of a coelacanth-class submersible, this streamlined bow is designed to allow a vessel to reach greater speeds underwater.
Comprising the top of a coelacanth-class submersible, this bridge is expansive and equipped with amenities to enable longer voyages.
Comprising the center of a coelacanth-class submersible, this ovoid hull is designed to be resilient against external water pressure and thereby raises maximum operating depth.
Comprising the rear end of a coelacanth-class submersible, this stern includes a hydrodynamic rudder for optimal lateral maneuverability.
A common (★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
An uncommon (★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A rare (★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A legendary (★★★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
A legendary (★★★★★) card used in the game Triple Triad.
It is unknown by whom or for what purpose this wooden idol carved in the likeness of the auspice Suzaku was created.

A uniquely crafted lens discovered somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

Two lenses can be traded for special headgear.

A uniquely crafted shaft discovered somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

Four shafts can be traded for special body gear.

A uniquely crafted crank discovered somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

Two cranks can be traded for special arm gear.

A uniquely crafted spring discovered somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

Four springs can be traded for special leg gear.

A uniquely crafted pedal discovered somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

Two pedals can be traded for special foot gear.

A uniquely crafted chain discovered somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

One chain can be traded for a special belt.

A uniquely crafted bolt discovered somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

One bolt can be traded for a special accessory.

Detailed records of past battles waged somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

Logs of the same type can be traded for special gear.

Detailed records of past battles waged somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

Logs of the same type can be traded for special gear or materials.

Detailed records of past battles waged somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

Logs of the same type can be traded for special gear or materials.

Detailed records of past battles waged somewhere within the Interdimensional Rift.

Logs of the same type can be traded for special gear.
A remarkable crystalline fragment within which can be seen images from another world.

A lubricant concocted by a certain Garlond Ironworks consultant that, when applied to weapons of similar origin, heightens their attributes by smoothing interactions between their many interlocking parts.
A sturdy fiber devised by a certain Garlond Ironworks consultant for the purpose of heightening the attributes of armor of his own design.

A fixing agent concocted by a certain Garlond Ironworks consultant that, when applied to accessories of similar origin, heightens their attributes by rebuffing vapor penetration and insulating delicate internal mechanisms.
A note of promise received from Rowena for the delivery of Allagan tomestones of genesis or poetics.

The exacting specifications to which this tomestone was made, along with its half-deciphered contents, have led Ironworks engineers to believe that it was manufactured for exclusive use by the Allagan armed forces.

Fisher legend has there was once a mighty liopleurodon who, unsatisfied with a diet of Namazu, is said to have set its sights on plumper prey─namely a portly Lalafellin regent with a penchant for skinny dipping in the warm waters near Hells' Lid. However, the fish quickly learned the limits of its maw's gape, and crestfallen, abandoned the king, a crown-shaped scar on its upper lip its only prize. But rather than sulk, this beast from the deep spent the rest of its life devouring creatures far larger than it, and now, five thousand summers later, the descendant of that legendary pioneer polishes off Plainsfolk like they were popotoes, proving once and for all...life truly does find a way.

This massive predator has haunted the nightmares of Gyr Abanians for generations as the legendary “impaler of Timmon Beck,” thanks to its centuries-old legacy of terrorizing smallfolk attempting to do their washing.
Perhaps the greatest catch to be found at Grymm & Enid, the drepanaspis is so rare that, until now, no one was sure that one <Emphasis>could</Emphasis> be found at Grymm & Enid.
The size of the growths on this stethacanthus indicate that it may be the oldest still in existence─and also why it has come to be known as the “Loch Seld monster.”
This legendary king of the deep is known to all who have ever come near the Ruby Price─and yes, it is a <Emphasis>dragon</Emphasis>. Or at least it quite closely resembles one.
Though beautiful, this polychromatic carp ruled Prism Lake with an iron fin...until now.

Not so much a lord as a god of Dotharl Khaa, this particular specimen is thought to be a blessing sent by the Dusk Mother and Dawn Father themselves. As such, this catch might be best left unboasted of.

It is known to inspire all who read it, granting a temporary 100% boost to experience points earned from gathering activities (up to a maximum of 4,000,000 points).

Named for the markings that run down each side of its head, although its circular maw lined with serrated teeth is perhaps more worthy of attention.
While the texture of many species of oyster could be described as “creamy,” there is only one specifically named for this quality.
These rare bivalve mollusks are harvested more for their shells than for their meat, as the inner nacre can be used as a form of naturally occurring mirror.

Fish can adapt to the most unlikely of environments, as this repulsive sand-dweller amply proves. It spends most of its adult life burrowing through the sands of Amh Araeng searching for moisture and snaring unsuspecting prey in its fearsome jaws.
The beautiful markings and coloration of this elusive species are known to cause pangs of guilt in those who catch one, shortly before they bash it over the head and gut it.

This species native to the Tempest is believed by locals to possess the ability to control the elements using some form of innate magic. This may, however, be no more than a ruse invented by the Ondo to keep intruders out of their waters.
Will this specimen yield a breakthrough in the search for the samiel? Only time and effort will tell...

“A steaming, fly-ridden pile of excrement is a veritable repository of knowledge.”
─Qeshi-Rae
Whatever bit into this plant part can only be described as massive.
The possibility cannot be denied: something massive this way came.
Shed by what is believed to be an ancient creature, this shred of skin may well shed light on the samiel.
This aetherially charged sand is a key ingredient in the preparation of glamour dispeller.

A rough-hewn horn of petrified bone that, when blown, emits a somber tone that summons a lumbering triceratops.

Gaze upon the visage of a ruthless killer.

Use item to acquire the black hayate minion.

Marvel as it melts into your surrounds...and then panic as you realize you cannot find it again.

Use item to acquire the chameleon minion.

Possessed of a superior sense of balance.

Use item to acquire the armadillo bowler minion.

Tremble, child of man, for a creature of purest divinity wiggleth before thee.

Use item to acquire the Great Serpent of Ronka minion.

Is it small or is it big? You be the judge.

Use item to acquire the micro gigantender minion.

Small on size but massive on appetite.

Use item to acquire the clionid larva minion.

Do not attempt to put on your feet.

Use item to acquire the bitty duckbill minion.

A mystery better left unsolved.

Use item to acquire the giant beaver minion.

Complete with her flute and her senses.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Suzaku minion.

Irrational behavior detected. Further observation required.

Use item to acquire the wind-up Omega-M minion.

Combat role allocation test initiated. Analyzing...

Use item to acquire the wind-up Omega-F minion.

Said to be named for a pixie...unless you ask the pixies, who adamantly deny that any of their kind would ever have borne such a ludicrous name.

Use item to acquire the tinker's bell minion.

Its tail tastes like nectar...but you wouldn't know such things.

Use item to acquire the tiny echevore minion.

An unflappable bird possessed of a regal air...or perhaps simply a condescending one.

Use item to acquire the shoebill minion.

Illusory and therefore incapable of invoking any history-shattering consequences...right?

Use item to acquire the butterfly effect minion.

A darling, diminutive, dwarf-made...automaton.

Use item to acquire the ironfrog ambler minion.

Having repented its sins, it poses no danger.

Use item to acquire the forgiven hate minion.

column5: A devilish─though, admittedly, industrious─imp is thought to have made this slightly burnt biscuit shaped like a pumpkin head. One can only wonder what ingredients it contains, but as the people of Eorzea have been consuming these for years now with no ill effects beyond mild disappointment, they're probably not <Emphasis>too</Emphasis> horrific.
A pair of sturdy-yet-flexible gauntlets, designed to protect the hands from amaro bites.
A metal jar designed to keep worms fresh.
A fearsome metal weapon ending in three deadly looking spikes.
An amulet imbued with magic-resisting properties.
A set of materials needed to forge an intricate censer.
A solid metal censer of exquisite design.
A set of materials needed to forge an enchanting ring.
This finely wrought ring gleams with an almost sorcerous sheen.
Materials for repairing the canvas of the painting of Dampsole, Lakeland.
Materials for repairing the upholstery of the Voeburtite jewelry box.

The modification component that you hope will make Harig's lute sing as it once did.

Wholesome and easily digestible food for delicate amaro stomachs.
A comforting and invigorating vegetable and herb medley sure to have a restorative effect on both body and soul.
This dish of assorted greens will be instantly recognizable to any Berube skipper as the feed it was raised on.
Assorted ingredients for the preparation of desserts that will please the fae─such as sugar, sugar, and more sugar.
A variety of colorful confections to excite and delight the fae.
Assorted ingredients for the traditional amaro feed used by the Zun.
The traditional nutritious feed used by the Zun in raising healthy and happy amaro.

A rustic interior wall of simple wooden boards.
Flooring of evenly laid red brick that calls to mind urban spaces.
A bright and elegant ceiling light identical to those found throughout the Crystarium.
This elegant lamp, its natural motifs rendered in polished and painted metal and glass, will make a master of white magic feel right at home.

The reason that the sight of one of these warmly glowing light fixtures puts those with a penchant for healing so very much at ease will ever remain a mystery to people not versed in the secrets of white magic.
A large white partition with a marble-carved arch creating a portal through the center.
A yellow curtain gathered with a polished wooden fastener.
At least they're clean. Ish.
One of Il Mheg's many brilliant butterflies, mounted for display.
All manner of foodstuffs could be inside this plain brown shopping bag. ...Hopefully they did not require refrigeration.
The requisite weapons and traps for a foray into the wilds.
The requisite defensive and offensive accoutrements for combat.
Though this is neither real crystal nor a real windowpane, the rear lighting makes it appear sumptuous all the same.
A cream-colored partition with a white marble baseboard.
A wrought-iron seat identical to those found throughout the Crystarium.
A small citrus tree in an elegant wrought-iron vessel.
A warmly glowing iron kitchen stove.
This wall-mounted hanger provides easy access to pots and pans for use in cooking or punctuating one's statements with loud clanging noises.
This metal teapot comes with a serving tray, cup, and jar of tea leaves for your convenience.
Rather unfortunately for those attempting to get anywhere on time, this chronometer features a mesmerizing pattern and pendulum.
A hand-painted notice advertising the Eorzean Nimble Warrior course.
A hand-painted notice advertising the sorcery and spooks of All Saints' Wake.
A convenient clockwork contraption for the counting and keeping of currency.

A branching golden vessel harboring enough fruit to feed two Crystarium families or one Eulmoran hedonist for several days.

As the person to whom these eyeglasses belonged is now without eyeglasses, he will likely never be able to find them again and is probably wandering around bumping into things at this very moment.
A circular patch of rug upon which colorful flowers have been enchanted to grow. Not recommended for those with seasonal allergies.

This unobtrusive lantern provides necessary illumination without sacrificing ambience.
An alchemical flame burns perpetually within the metal-and-glass casing of this lantern.

Whether this plush toy can actually restore its owner to good health as is rumored is unclear, but it certainly does look as it if would like to.

Nothing says “summer” like the dissonant tinkling of half a dozen wind chimes at once.

Plants from these seeds will burst into bloom in brightly colored clusters─like fireworks in your very own home, without the danger of burning down your very own home.
